'''Ariadna Thalía Sodi Miranda<!--Please add reliable sources confirming that she has taken her husbands surname.-->''' ({{IPA-es|aˈɾjaðna taˈli.a ˈsoði miˈɾanda}}; born 26 August 1971), known [[Mononymous person|mononymously]] as '''Thalía''', is a Mexican singer and actress.<ref name="Billboard2014">{{cite magazine|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/6312343/thalia-on-amore-mio-album-macys-clothing-line-tommy-mottola|title=Latin Pop Queen Thalia on Her New Album 'Amore Mio': 'I've Started a Brand-New Career, With No Ties or Taboos'|magazine=Billboard|date=November 2014|access-date=9 February 2015|quote=For millions of Latin fans, Thalia is a brand onto herself: Latin pop queen, glam businesswoman, erstwhile soap opera star.}}</ref> Referred to as the "[[Honorific nicknames in popular music|Queen of Latin Pop]]",<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.grammy.com/grammys/news/ricky-martin-thalía-5-latin-autobiographies-you-should-read|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200617105143/https://www.grammy.com/grammys/news/ricky-martin-thal%C3%ADa-5-latin-autobiographies-you-should-read|archive-date=17 June 2020|title=Ricky Martin To Thalía: 5 Latin Autobiographies You Should Read|publisher=[[Grammy Award]]|access-date=1 January 2021|date=29 September 2017|first=Renée|last=Fabian}}</ref> she is considered one of the most successful and influential Mexican artists.<ref name="Oye">{{cite news|url=http://www.oyemexico.com/nota/25-mexicanos-mas-influyentes-en-la-musica/|title=25 mexicanos más influyentes en la música|work=Oyemexico.com|access-date=10 August 2012|language=es|archive-date=8 December 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121208213808/http://www.oyemexico.com/nota/25-mexicanos-mas-influyentes-en-la-musica/|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref name="Televisa">{{cite news|url=http://especiales.televisa.com/musica/noticias/512948/thalia-con-nuevo-disco/|title=Thalía con nuevo disco|work=[[Televisa]]|access-date=27 August 2012|language=es|archive-date=4 March 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304054233/http://especiales.televisa.com/musica/noticias/512948/thalia-con-nuevo-disco/|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref name="TV Azteca">{{cite news|url=http://www.azteca.com/notas/vengalaalegria/128322/thalia-una-de-las-mexicanas-mas-tocadas|title=Ellas son las mexicanas más tocadas|work=[[Azteca (multimedia company)|Azteca]]|author=Ana Karen Grande Benavides|date=30 August 2012|access-date=10 August 2012|language=es|archive-date=29 October 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131029194540/http://www.azteca.com/notas/vengalaalegria/128322/thalia-una-de-las-mexicanas-mas-tocadas|url-status=dead}}</ref> Having sold around 25 million records worldwide, she is one of the best-selling Latin music artists of all-time.<ref name="wwsales">{{cite news|date=15 October 2019 |title=Thalía: una vida de telenovela signada por la pasión, el éxito y la tragedia|work=[[La Nación]]|url=https://www.lanacion.com.ar/espectaculos/personajes/thalia-vida-telenovela-signada-amor-exito-tragedia-nid2295802|access-date=7 January 2021|first= Cynthia |last=Caccia }}</ref> Aside from her native Spanish, Thalía has also sung in English, French, Portuguese and [[Filipino language|Tagalog]].<ref name="Billboard 1997">{{cite magazine|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=oxMEAAAAMBAJ&q=Thal%C3%ADa+to+release+Arrasando&pg=RA1-PA30|title=THE BILLBOARD STAR AWARD : Thalía <nowiki>|</nowiki> The Mexican Singer/Actress Has Risen From Kiddie Pop To Soap Operas To International Status|magazine=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|date=March 2011|access-date=11 August 2012}}</ref>

She has received [[List of awards and nominations received by Thalía|numerous accolades]], including five [[Billboard Latin Music Awards|''Billboard'' Latin Music Awards]], eight [[Lo Nuestro Awards]], as well as seven [[Latin Grammy Award]] nominations<ref>{{cite web|url=http://hollywood.patch.com/groups/arts-and-entertainment/p/thalia-queen-of-latin-pop-to-receive-hollywood-walk-of-fame-star |title=Patch |date=4 December 2013 |publisher=Hollywood.patch.com |access-date=5 August 2014}}</ref> and their special "President's Merit Award" in 2019.<ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://www.billboard.com/amp/articles/news/awards/8543732/latin-grammys-2019-highlights-bad-bunny-juanes-rosalia-thalia|title=2019 Latin Grammy Highlights|magazine=Billboard|date=15 November 2019|access-date=15 November 2019}}</ref> She has collaborated with multiple artists, such as [[Tony Bennett]], [[Michael Bublé]], [[Robbie Williams]], [[Marc Anthony]], [[Laura Pausini]], [[Romeo Santos]], [[Maluma]], [[Fat Joe]], and [[Carlos Vives]].

As an actress, Thalía starred in a variety of successful [[telenovelas]] that aired in over 180 countries with an estimated audience of 2 billion people according to [[UNICEF]],<ref name="Houston">{{cite news|url=http://www.chron.com/spanish/entertainment/article/Thal-a-busca-la-liberaci-n-1726321.php|title=Thalia busca la liberación|last=Dorantes|first=David|work=[[Houston Chronicle]]|date=27 September 2009|access-date=10 August 2012|language=es}}</ref><ref name="UNICEF"/> which led to her being referred to as the "Queen of [[telenovelas]]" by the mass media.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.nytimes.com/1996/08/27/world/mere-soap-opera-it-s-mexican-magic-in-tagalog.html | work=The New York Times | first=Edward A. | last=Gargan | title=Mere Soap Opera? It's Mexican Magic (in Tagalog) | date=27 August 1996}}</ref> The global impact of her novelas helped her to popularize her music in non-Spanish speaking territories and markets in Europe and Asia. The Mexican media company [[Televisa]] has named her the best-paid telenovela actress in history,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.laprensa.com.bo/diario/entretendencias/escena/20111018/thalia-reina-de-las-novelas_9504_15909.html |title=Thalia, reina de las novelas |publisher=Laprensa.com.bo |date=18 October 2011 |access-date=5 August 2014 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131029192831/http://www.laprensa.com.bo/diario/entretendencias/escena/20111018/thalia-reina-de-las-novelas_9504_15909.html |archive-date=29 October 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=e-jJZGzobpI&feature=relmfu  |archive-url=https://ghostarchive.org/varchive/youtube/20211221/e-jJZGzobpI |archive-date=2021-12-21 |url-status=live|title=Thalia – La Historia Detras Del Mito Pt. 3 of 5 |publisher=YouTube |date=13 September 2011 |access-date=5 August 2014}}{{cbignore}}</ref> while ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'' names her the most widely recognized Spanish-speaking soap star in the world.<ref name="Start"/>

Considered a Latin pop icon,<ref>{{cite journal| url=https://books.google.com/books?id=6iU4AQAAIAAJ&q=Thal%C3%ADa+pop+icon| title=Studies in Latin American Popular Culture| publisher=Department of Spanish and Portuguese, University of Arizona| year=2002|page=222|quote=Telenovelas starring the pop icon Thalia are typical of the pure Cinderella variant of the Mexican soap opera, the novela rosa.}}</ref> [[Ocean Drive (magazine)|''Ocean Drive'']] called Thalía as "the biggest star Mexico has exported in the last decades".<ref name="OceanDrive"/> She was included in ''Billboard''{{'}}s Greatest Latin Artists of All Time in 2020 and in ''[[People En Español]]''{{'}}s The 100 most iconic Hispanic entertainers of all time in 2008.<ref name="BBLatin">{{cite magazine|url=https://www.billboard.com/charts/greatest-of-all-time-latin-artists|title=GREATEST OF ALL TIME LATIN ARTISTS|magazine=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|date=October 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201103001637/https://www.billboard.com/charts/greatest-of-all-time-latin-artists|access-date=3 December 2020|archive-date=3 November 2020}}</ref><ref name="PHispanis"/> On 5 December 2013, she was honored with a star on the [[Hollywood Walk of Fame]] as a recognition for her achievements in the music industry.<ref name="Huffington Post Walk">{{cite news|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2012/06/26/thalia-hollywood-walk-of-fame_n_1628329.html|title=Thalía To Get Star On Hollywood Walk Of Fame|last=Lopez|first=Michael|work=Huffington Post|date=26 June 2012|access-date=10 August 2012}}</ref><ref name="Walk of fame Tribue Pakistan">{{cite news|url=http://tribune.com.pk/story/398205/honourees-announced-for-hollywood-walk-of-fame-2013/|title=Honourees announced for Hollywood Walk of Fame 2013|work=[[The Express Tribune]]|date=23 June 2012|access-date=10 September 2012}}</ref> As a businesswoman, Thalía enjoyed success with a fashion brand (having signed a deal with [[Macy's]]), as well she had her own nationally syndicated radio show and is the author of four books, including her memoir. During her career, Thalía has been involved in humanitarian causes and is an [[List of UNICEF Goodwill Ambassadors|UNICEF Mexico Ambassador]] since 2016.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.unicef.org/es/comunicados-prensa/la-reconocida-actriz-y-cantante-thal%C3%ADa-es-nombrada-embajadora-de-buena-voluntad|title=La reconocida actriz y cantante Thalía es nombrada Embajadora de Buena Voluntad de UNICEF México|publisher=[[UNICEF]]}}</ref>

==Early life==
[[File:Lago de Chapultepec V.jpg|thumb|Thalía was born in Mexico City.]]
Thalía was born on 26 August 1971 in [[Mexico City]]. She is the youngest of five daughters of Yolanda Miranda Mange (d. 2011), a painter who was Thalía's manager from 1980 to 1999 and Ernesto Sodi Pallares (d. 1977), a scientist, doctor of [[pathology]], [[criminologist]] and writer. Her four sisters are [[Laura Zapata]] (daughter of Guillermo Zapata Pérez de Utrera), Federica, Gabriela and Ernestina Sodi.{{citation needed|date=May 2021}}

When she turned one, Thalía appeared in her first TV commercial in Mexico. At the age of four, she began taking ballet and piano classes at the [[Conservatorio Nacional de Música (Mexico)]].<ref>{{cite web|first=Por |last=Notimex |url=http://www.zocalo.com.mx/seccion/articulo/celebrara-thalia-su-cumpleanos-40 |title=Celebrará Thalía su cumpleaños 40 [Thalía&#93; – 25/08/2011 {{pipe}} Periódico Zócalo |publisher=Zocalo.com.mx |date=25 August 2011 |access-date=5 August 2014}}</ref> Her father suffered from [[diabetes]] and died in 1977 when Thalía was six years old.{{citation needed|date=May 2021}}

Years later, Thalía admitted publicly that her father's death had traumatized her drastically, since she had lost her voice for a whole year. This led to her being diagnosed with [[childhood disintegrative disorder]] (CDH), which belongs to a series of developmental disorders related to [[autism spectrum]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.casatelenovela.com/2008/04/la_cantante_y_actriz_thalia_fu.html|title=CasaTelenovela – Las Telenovelas al momento – el porque y el quién|access-date=31 October 2014|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080409164332/http://www.casatelenovela.com/2008/04/la_cantante_y_actriz_thalia_fu.html|archive-date=9 April 2008}}</ref> She has said that she had psychological therapy for a few years.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.generaccion.com/noticia/127628/thalia-enmudecio-tras-muerte-su-padre |title=Thalia enmudeció tras la muerte de su padre |publisher=Generaccion.com |access-date=5 August 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tvynovelas.com/noticias/356657/thalia-confiesa-estuvo-muda-ano|work=TVyNovelas.com|title=Revista TVyNovelas|publisher=Tvynovelas.com|access-date=5 August 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121210224536/http://www.tvynovelas.com/noticias/356657/thalia-confiesa-estuvo-muda-ano|archive-date=10 December 2012|url-status=dead}}</ref> She has reportedly mentioned that she was a victim of [[bullying]] as a child because of the loss of her father.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.today.com/id/45148867/ns/today-today_books/t/growing-stronger-thalia-shares-her-story/ |title='Growing Stronger': Thalia shares her story – today > books |website=TODAY.com |access-date=27 August 2016}}</ref>

Thalía attended [[Lycée Franco-Mexicain]] elementary school, where she learned to speak French fluently at a very young age.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://musica.univision.com/artistas/thalia/biografia |title=Biografía de Thalía {{pipe}} Univision Música |publisher=Musica.univision.com |access-date=5 August 2014}}</ref> In 1976, a year before her father's death, she had a guest appearance in the Mexican film ''La guerra de los pasteles'' ("War of Cakes"), although her name doesn't appear in the film credits.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0180724/fullcredits#cast|title=La guerra de los pasteles (1979)|work=IMDb|access-date=31 October 2014}}</ref>

==Music career==
===1981–1989: Career beginnings and the Timbiriche era===
In 1981, when Thalía was nine years old, she was incorporated as a vocalist in a children's group named Pac Man, which was formed to participate in a popular music festival known as ''Juguemos a cantar'' ("Let's play like we're singing"), a TV program by [[Televisa]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mx.hola.com/biografias/thalia/biografia/ |title=Thalía. Noticias, fotos y biografía de Thalía |publisher=Mx.hola.com |access-date=5 August 2014}}</ref> Later, Pac Man changed their band name to "Din-Din". Thalía performed various times along with Din-Din in occasional events and parties, touring all over Mexico. The band recorded a total of 4 studio albums between 1982 and 1983 (''En acción'', ''Recordando el Rock and Roll'', ''Somos alguien muy especial'' and ''Pitubailando''), and later it was disbanded.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://eil.com/shop/moreinfo.asp?catalogid=334256 |title=Thalia Din-Din En Accion Mexico vinyl LP album (LP record) (334256) |publisher=Eil.com |date=14 March 2002 |access-date=5 August 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://eil.com/shop/moreinfo.asp?catalogid=387057 |title=Thalia Pitubailando Mexico 12" vinyl single (12 inch record / Maxi-single) (387057) |publisher=Eil.com |date=14 March 2002 |access-date=5 August 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://eil.com/shop/moreinfo.asp?catalogid=387069 |title=Thalia Somos Alguien Muy Especial Mexico vinyl LP album (LP record) (387069) |publisher=Eil.com |date=14 March 2002 |access-date=5 August 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://eil.com/shop/moreinfo.asp?catalogid=387050 |title=Thalia Recordando El Rock And Roll Mexico 12" vinyl single (12 inch record / Maxi-single) (387050) |publisher=Eil.com |date=14 March 2002 |access-date=5 August 2014}}</ref>

After Din-Din broke up in 1984, Thalía participated as a solo artist in two annual music festivals of ''Juguemos a cantar''. In 1984, she placed second there with her interpretation of "Moderna niña del rock" ("Modern rock girl"); this brought her the opportunity to participate in the chorus of the popular musical ''Vaselina'', a child version of the successful musical ''[[Grease (musical)|Grease]]'', in which the band [[Timbiriche]] was acting and singing. The line-up of the band consisted of Sasha Sökol, Benny Ibarra, Erik Rubín, Diego Schoening, Mariana Garza and [[Paulina Rubio]]. [[Timbiriche]] was highly promoted at the time by [[Televisa]], one of the most massive media enterprises globally and the most important in the Spanish-speaking world. Some time later, Thalía obtained the protagonist role of Sandy Dee in the musical, and she performed in 500 theater presentations of ''Vaselina'' along with [[Timbiriche]].

In 1986, after the departure of Sasha Sökol from Timbiriche, Thalía became a member of the band. By that time, Timbiriche had already recorded five albums. In 1987, she made her TV acting debut in an episode of the [[telenovela]] ''Pobre señorita Limantour''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0211843/fullcredits#cast|title=La pobre Señorita Limantour (TV Series 1983– )|work=IMDb|access-date=31 October 2014}}</ref> In the same year, she recorded with [[Timbiriche]] the principal theme of the [[young adult fiction|juvenile]] [[telenovela]] ''[[Quinceañera (telenovela)|Quinceañera]]'' ("Fifteen-year-old"), in which Thalía was the co-protagonist with the role of Beatriz.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.alma-latina.net/Quinceanera/Quinceanera.shtml |title=Quinceańera – telenovela |publisher=Alma-latina.net |access-date=5 August 2014}}</ref> The TV series was awarded as the "Best telenovela" by "Premios TVyNovelas" in 1988 and Thalía was awarded as "the best new actress of 1988".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=uWQELqT9kGo  |archive-url=https://ghostarchive.org/varchive/youtube/20211221/uWQELqT9kGo |archive-date=2021-12-21 |url-status=live|title=THALIA recibe premio tvnovelas por actriz revelacion en quinceañera |publisher=YouTube |date=13 February 2010 |access-date=5 August 2014}}{{cbignore}}</ref>

With [[Timbiriche]], Thalía recorded four studio albums: ''[[Timbiriche VII]]'' (1987), the double album ''[[Timbiriche VIII & IX]]'' (1988) and ''Los clásicos de Timbiriche'' (1989). The last one is a compilation of the band's greatest hits, recorded originally in 1987, with new symphonic arrangements as it included the participation of Mexico's philharmonic orchestra.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www2.esmas.com/ritmoson-latino/artistas/251843?page=1 |title=Ritmoson |publisher=.esmas.com |access-date=5 August 2014}}</ref> In 1989, Thalía departed from Timbiriche.<ref>{{cite web|author=Eunice Martínez Arias |url=http://www.elsiglodetorreon.com.mx/noticia/284817.vuelven-a-vivir-el-exito.html |title=Vuelven a vivir el éxito |publisher=Elsiglodetorreon.com.mx |date=6 July 2007 |access-date=5 August 2014}}</ref> In that year, she also starred in another TV series, ''Luz y sombra'' ("Light and shadow"), which was her first protagonist role.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0211824/|title=Luz y sombra (TV Series 1989– )|work=IMDb|access-date=31 October 2014}}</ref> Some time later she visited Los Angeles to take English courses in the University of California. She also attended music, singing, acting and dancing classes before beginning her career as a solo artist.

===1990–1993: First albums as a solo artist===
In 1990, Thalía returned to Mexico and released her first studio album as a [[solo artist]], self-titled  ''[[Thalía (1990 album)|Thalía]]'', which was produced by Alfredo Díaz Ordaz, and published by [[Fonovisa Records|Fonovisa]], [[Televisa]]'s record label. From that album, she released a total of four singles that became radio hits: "Amarillo Azul", "[[Pienso en Ti]]", "[[Un Pacto Entre los Dos]]" and "[[Saliva (Thalía song)|Saliva]]". The last two tracks were co-written by her and Díaz Ordaz and they were considered as provocative at the time ("Un Pacto Entre Los Dos" was even labeled as a song with occult Satan-worship lyrics by various [[Far-right politics|far-right parties]]).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.revista-contacto.info/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=9622:thalia-precursora-de-lady-gaga&catid=117:ultimas-noticias&Itemid=596|title=revista-contacto.info|date=22 June 2013|url-status=bot: unknown|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130622215005/http://www.revista-contacto.info/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=9622:thalia-precursora-de-lady-gaga&catid=117:ultimas-noticias&Itemid=596|archive-date=22 June 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://musica.univision.com/fotos/curiosas/slideshow/2011-08-25/thalia-40-anos-canciones-trayectoria-fotos-cumpleanos |title=Thalía. 40 años, 40 canciones – Univision Música |publisher=Musica.univision.com |access-date=5 August 2014}}</ref>

In September 1991, Thalía released her second studio album, ''[[Mundo de cristal]]'', which marks Thalía's last project in collaboration with Alfredo Díaz Ordaz. Four songs became radio singles from the album, and all of them had big radio impact in Mexico. Due to the success of the singles, the album was certified as double gold in Thalía's native country, Mexico. In the same year, Thalía was co-presenter of the late Spanish show ''VIP Noche'', along with Spanish presenter Emilio Aragón, produced by [[Telecinco]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0321004/fullcredits#cast|title=VIP noche (TV Series 1990–1992)|work=IMDb|access-date=31 October 2014}}</ref>

In October 1992, she released her third studio album and her last under the same label, entitled ''[[Love (Thalía album)|Love]]'', which was recorded in Spain and was produced by Luis Carlos Esteban. The album spread six singles, that had huge radio impact: "[[Sangre (Thalía song)|Sangre]]", "[[Love (Thalía song)|Love]]", "[[Maria Mercedes (song)|María Mercedes]]" (official theme of the TV series), "No Trates de Engañarme", "Flor de Juventud", and "La Vida en Rosa" ([[La vie en rose]]), the last one being a Spanish-French cover of the classic French song originally performed by [[Edith Piaf]]. Thalía wrote the song "Sangre" inspired in Díaz Ordaz, with whom she had broken up her sentimental relation. The album was praised by the critics, as it was an artistic evolution for Thalía, who experimented for the first time in different [[music genres]], especially [[electronic music]]. The album reached number 15 on [[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard's]] ''[[Latin Pop Albums]]'' in 1993.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.allrovi.com/music/album/love-mw0000172049|archive-url=https://archive.today/20120702214934/http://www.allrovi.com/music/album/love-mw0000172049|url-status=dead|title=Listen to Love by Thalía – Album Reviews, Credits, and Awards – AllRo...|date=2 July 2012|archive-date=2 July 2012}}</ref> In Mexico, it sold over 200,000 copies in the first month upon its release and very soon it reached the platinum and gold certification, while it was a commercial success all over Latin America.

===1994–1999: International breakout===
In 1994, during the successful transmission of ''[[Marimar (Mexican telenovela)|Marimar]]'', Thalía signed a contract with the record label [[EMI]] to prepare her fourth studio album that was entitled ''[[En éxtasis]]''. The album was released in October 1995. ''En éxtasis'' was produced with the aid of celebrated producers such as [[Emilio Estefan, Jr.]] (husband of the famous Cuban singer [[Gloria Estefan]]) and Óscar López.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=STjcB_f7CVcC&q=thalia&pg=PA835|title=Encyclopedia of Latino Popular Culture|access-date=31 October 2014|isbn=9780313332104|last1=Candelaria|first1=Cordelia|year=2004}}</ref> The album spawned a total of seven singles including "[[Piel morena]]", "[[Amándote]]", "[[Maria la del Barrio (song)|María la del barrio]]", "[[Quiero hacerte el amor]]", "[[Gracias a Dios (song)|Gracias a Dios]], "[[Me Faltas Tú]]" and "[[Lágrimas (Thalía song)|Lágrimas]]". [[Piel morena]] became a huge international hit<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.allmusic.com/artist/p29449/charts-awards/billboard-singles|title=Thalía – Awards – AllMusic|first=Jason|last=Birchmeier|work=AllMusic|access-date=31 October 2014}}</ref> apart from being voted as the best Spanish song ever in the United States from a poll released by mass media company [[Univision]]. It must also be added that Thalía was more oriented to the [[latin pop]] music genre in that album, even though it was influenced by various music genres. Amandote became a number 1 hit in various radio stations in the Philippines in 1996, along with her phenomenal superstardom accompanied by her historic Manila tour. It was described by Philippine media as tantamount to that of Pope John Paul II's 1995 Manila visit.
{{check quotation}}The broadcast of the [[telenovelas]] ''[[María Mercedes (telenovela)|María Mercedes]]'', ''[[Marimar (Mexican telenovela)|Marimar]]'' and ''[[María la del barrio]]'' had already converted Thalía to a global television phenomenon by the end of 1996. In January 1997, she released her first compilation album entitled ''[[Nandito Ako (album)|Nandito Ako]]'', which contains four songs recorded in Filipino, five English versions from various tracks from the album [[En éxtasis]] and a Spanish remix of the song [[Amándote]]. The only single that was released from this album was ''Nandito Ako''. The album became a commercial success in the Philippines as a result of Thalía's growing popularity, reaching platinum status set by the [[Philippine Association of the Record Industry]]. [[En éxtasis]] was her first album that was released worldwide, reaching gold, platinum or multi-platinum status in more than 20 countries.

In July 1997, Thalía's fifth studio album was released, under the title ''[[Amor a la mexicana]]'', produced again by [[Emilio Estefan]], and including songs that became classic over the years like "[[Mujer Latina]]", "[[De dónde soy]]", "[[Por amor (Thalía song)|Por amor]]", "[[Noches sin luna]]" and "[[Amor a la Mexicana (song)|Amor a la mexicana]]". The album became a pure commercial success,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/amor-a-la-mexicana-r278142/charts-awards|title=Amor a la Mexicana – Thalía – Awards – AllMusic|work=AllMusic|access-date=31 October 2014}}</ref> while the first single of the album ("[[Amor a la Mexicana (song)|Amor a la mexicana]]") became a number one hit in 14 countries. With Amor a la mexicana, Thalía was able to bring her music and establish her projects in difficult markets like those of France, [[Belgium]], [[Switzerland]], [[Greece]], [[Hungary]], [[Turkey]], [[Poland]], [[Portugal]], Italy and all the Spanish-speaking countries.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://anodis.com/galeria.asp?id=7 |title=Anodis.com |website=Anodis.com |access-date=27 August 2016 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131029191500/http://anodis.com/galeria.asp?id=7 |archive-date=29 October 2013}}</ref>

After the success of ''Amor a la mexicana'', Thalía recorded the Spanish and Portuguese versions of the song "Journey to the Past", produced by [[Atlantic Records]], as a part of the soundtrack of the [[Fox Animation Studios]] movie ''[[Anastasia (1997 film)|Anastasia]]'' (1997).

In the following year, she starred for the first time in a movie in English, named "Mambo Café", written and directed by Reuben González.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://findarticles.com/p/articles/mi_m0EIN/is_1998_Nov_16/ai_53220016/ |title=CBSi |website=FindArticles.com |access-date=27 August 2016 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151018143758/http://findarticles.com/p/articles/mi_m0EIN/is_1998_Nov_16/ai_53220016/ |archive-date=18 October 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thefreelibrary.com/%27Mambo+Cafe%27+Wraps+Principle+Photography%3B+Kushner-Locke+to+Distribute...-a053625991|title='Mambo Cafe' Wraps Principle Photography; Kushner-Locke to Distribute Internationally.|access-date=31 October 2014}}</ref> ''Mambo Café'' premiered in January 2000 in Mexico, Greece and Russia, distributed by Kushner Locke Entertainment.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www2.eluniversal.com.mx/pls/impreso/noticia.html?id_nota=7847&tabla=espectaculos|title=El Universal|website=Eluniversal.com.mx|access-date=31 October 2014|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121022154837/http://www2.eluniversal.com.mx/pls/impreso/noticia.html?id_nota=7847&tabla=espectaculos|archive-date=22 October 2012}}</ref>

In 1999, after ''Mambo Café'', Thalía returned in television with [[telenovela]] ''[[Rosalinda (telenovela)|Rosalinda]]''. "Rosalinda" was considered to be [[Televisa]]'s most expensive production ever by that time, as well as the most exported in foreign countries, as it was sold in over 180 countries. In an interview of that period Thalía had commented: "The telenovelas are the ones that opened the doors of the world for me, because the audience of telenovelas is much more passionate than the audience of cinema. What's more, television is free".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.terra.com.mx/entretenimiento/articulo/15327/Thalia+llena+su+mundo.htm|title=Terra – Thalía llena su mundo – Famosos – Entretenimiento|website=Terra.com.mx|access-date=31 October 2014|archive-date=12 April 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130412050700/http://www.terra.com.mx/entretenimiento/articulo/15327/Thalia+llena+su+mundo.htm|url-status=dead}}</ref>

===2000–2005: Crossover and first tour in the United States===
Emilio Estefan also produced Thalía's sixth studio album, ''[[Arrasando]]'', released on 25 April 2000, which was successful. It spawned the singles "[[Entre el mar y una estrella]]", "[[Regresa a mí (Thalía song)|Regresa a mí]]", "[[Arrasando (song)|Arrasando]]" and "[[Reencarnación]]". Thalía was nominated in the [[Latin Grammy]] category as the "Best Female Pop Vocal Album". The album received one Latin Grammy nomination and it won in its category as the "Best Sound Engineered Album of the year". The singles of this album were huge hits. In 2001 she was nominated for her record ''Arrasando'' and won a Lo Nuestro award in the category of People's Prize, and was the first artist to whom an innovative award from Billboard Awards for Latin Music was given, the "Star Award".

On 4 May 2001, the President of the United States, [[George W. Bush]], invited her to a party celebrating [[Cinco de mayo]] organized at the [[White House]], where she interpreted a medley of popular Mexican songs with a Mexican mariachi band.

On 28 August 2001, expressing her love for her country of birth, Mexico, she released her album ''[[Thalía con banda: Grandes éxitos|Con Banda: Grandes Éxitos]]'': a "greatest hits" album, but recorded with the typical Mexican "banda" sound. "Amor a la Mexicana" banda version was released as a single. The album was nominated for a Latin Grammy for "Best Banda Album" at the 3rd Annual Latin Grammy Awards in 2002.

Her seventh studio album, self-titled ''[[Thalía (2002 album)|Thalía]]'', was released on 21 May 2002. It was largely written and produced by [[Estéfano]]. Buoyed by a pair of chart-topping singles ("[[Tú y Yo (Thalía song)|Tú y Yo]]" and "[[No me enseñaste]]") and a top-ten hit ("[[¿A quién le importa?]]") (cover of [[Alaska y Dinarama]]), this album hit number one for 6 consecutive weeks on the [[Top Latin Albums]] chart, reaching number eleven on the [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' 200]] chart and 2x Multi-Platinum status with sales in the U.S. of 200,000 copies. It was nominated in one [[Latin Grammy]] category – "[[Latin Grammy Award for Best Pop Vocal Album, Female|Female Pop Vocal Album]]", and in four [[2003 Latin Billboard Music Awards|Latin Billboard]] categories – "Pop Track Female" and "Tropical Track Female" for "No Me Enseñaste", [[2003 Latin Billboard Music Awards#Your World Award (Premio Tu Mundo)|"Your World Award"]], and [[2003 Latin Billboard Music Awards#Female|"Female Pop Album"]], for ''Thalía'', winning the last two awards. "No Me Enseñaste" reached at No. 1 in Billboard's [[Hot Latin Tracks]] chart.

On 25 February 2003, she released her first remix album, ''[[Thalía's Hits Remixed]]''. This album contains some [[remix]]es of her ''EMI era'' hits, such as "Amor a la Mexicana", "Piel Morena", "No Me Enseñaste" and "Tú y Yo." It also contains the English version of "Arrasando", called "It's My Party". Furthermore, it includes the previously unreleased medley that Thalía had recorded especially for her 2001 Latin Grammy Awards performance, but was later cancelled, due to the [[September 11 attacks]].

[[File:Thalía in concert2.jpg|thumb|Thalía in the ''High Voltage Tour'' Los Angeles concert on 14 May 2004]]
On 8 July 2003, Thalía released her eighth studio album and the first one in English, the self-titled ''[[Thalía (English album)|Thalía]]'', featuring the rapper [[Fat Joe]] in "[[I Want You (Thalía song)|I Want You/Me Pones Sexy]]". "[[Baby, I'm in Love|Baby, I'm in Love/Alguien Real]]", "[[Don't Look Back (Thalía song)|Don't Look Back]]" and "[[Cerca de ti (song)|Cerca De Ti]]" were singles too. The album landed at No. 11 in The Billboard 200. The song "[[I Want You (Thalía song)|I Want You]]" entered the [[American Top 40]] with Casey Kasem and even reached the top 10 during that year. The song also entered the American [[Billboard Top 100]] Singles Charts that year.<ref>{{Cite magazine |title=Thalía Hits Billboard|url={{BillboardURLbyName|artist=thalía|chart=all}} |magazine=Billboard}}</ref> She won an [[Winter Music Conference|International Dance Music Award]] for her club-hit "[[Dance Dance (The Mexican)]]".

On 10 February 2004, Thalía released her first official ''[[Greatest Hits (Thalía album)|Greatest Hits]]'' album, and "[[Cerca de ti (song)|Cerca de ti]]" and "[[Acción y Reacción]]" were the singles from this album. In April and May, she toured USA and Mexico with her "[[High Voltage Tour]]".

Her ninth studio album, ''[[El Sexto Sentido]]'', was released on 19 July 2005, and recorded mostly in Spanish, but with a few of the songs sung in English as well. It was reported to be the most expensive music album produced in Latin America in 2005. It had mild success, although the sound and the overall result make it one of her most integrated projects. "[[Amar sin ser amada]]" was the first single of the album and is considered as an infectious rock-edged [[tango music|tango]]-based song. "[[Un alma sentenciada]]", the second single of the album, is a feverish and, at points, hyperdramatic ballad. The explosive "[[Seducción (Thalía song)|Seducción]]" ("Seduction") and "Olvidame" were also released as singles, gaining considerable success. The album was also certified gold in Argentina, Greece and Mexico and double platinum in the United States.

===2006–2008: ''The Conexión Thalía Radio Show'', Lyme disease and ''Lunada''===
In 2006, the album received a reloaded version, ''[[El Sexto Sentido#El Sexto Sentido: Re+Loaded|El Sexto Sentido: Re+Loaded]]''. Thalía was the 'godmother' of ''[[Cantando Por Un Sueño (song)|Cantando Por Un Sueño]]'', a Mexican TV reality show. It was rumored she got paid 1 million dollars to perform. Thalía recorded the title song of the show, and it was included in the album. It was released in Mexico on 13 February 2006 (U.S. 6 June, Spain 29 May) and features four new songs, including a duet with the group [[Aventura (band)|Aventura]], "[[No, no, no (Thalía song)|No, No, No]]" which become a massive hit. "El Sexto Sentido" was nominated for one Latin Grammy as "Best Female Pop Vocal Album", it was also nominated in one Latin Billboard category – "Pop Female Album" and in eight Premios Juventud categories.

In 2006, Thalía became a U.S. citizen at a swearing-in ceremony in New York, where she resides with her husband. Under Mexican law she is allowed to retain her Mexican citizenship.<ref>{{Cite web |date=January 9, 2006 |title=Thalía ya es ciudadana estadounidense |url=https://peopleenespanol.com/article/thalia-ya-es-ciudadana-estadounidense/ |access-date=2022-04-13 |website=People en Español |language=es}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |date=2019-01-21 |title=Thalía y otras celebs latinas con nacionalidad estadounidense |url=https://www.hola.com/us-es/celebrities/galeria/2019012115898/famosos-latinos-nacionalidad-estadounidense-mz/1/ |access-date=2022-04-13 |website=hola.com |language=es-US}}</ref> She also received an award by her then record company [[EMI]], for sales of more than 10 million copies with all her discography with the company.<ref name="emiaward">{{cite news|url=https://peopleenespanol.com/article/thalia-recibe-disco-de-diamante/|title=Thalía recibe Disco de Diamante|work=[[People en Español]]|date=12 July 2006|access-date=22 March 2017|language=es|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304033252/http://peopleenespanol.com/article/thalia-recibe-disco-de-diamante/|archive-date=4 March 2016|url-status=live}}</ref>

In March 2007, Thalía also joined ABC Radio to start ''The Conexión Thalía Radio Show'', where she talks about music, fashion, news and political issues.

Afterwards, she was named one of the 50 Most Beautiful People in ''[[People en Español]]'' 2008 for a record-breaking seventh time where they called her their "Queen". She was once again featured in the 2010 edition for an eighth time.

In May 2008, Thalía's single "[[Ten Paciencia]]", was premiered on the internet.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://emitelevisa.com/portal/hgxpp001.aspx/?11,8,263,O,E,0,PAG;CONC;23;21;D;1793342;1;PAG;MNU;E;72;220;MNU;|title=EMI Televisa Blog {{pipe}} Just another WordPress site|date=29 October 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131029233824/http://emitelevisa.com/portal/hgxpp001.aspx/?11,8,263,O,E,0,PAG;CONC;23;21;D;1793342;1;PAG;MNU;E;72;220;MNU;|archive-date=29 October 2013}}</ref> Although, the single received a lukewarm response and did not perform well in the U.S. charts and Top 20 hits in Mexico, it was No. 1 in several countries of Latin America. Furthermore, her tenth studio album ''[[Lunada (album)|Lunada]]'', was released on 24 June 2008, and debuted at number eight in Mexico and peaked at number ten on the Billboard Top Latin Albums (U.S). It was the last Thalía's studio album released by [[EMI]].

Thalía later appeared on ''El Show De Cristina'', aired in late July by Univision's Spanish network to promote the album. According to Univision network, her appearance on the show received huge ratings, reaching No. 1 in both the Chicago and Miami markets. The show was said to have been viewed by over 87 million people in the US alone.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://thalia3arabia.blogspot.com/2008/08/thalia-and-cristina-show-scored-major.html |title=Thalia 3arabia>>Welcome ToThalia 3arabia, The Ultimate Sourse For Thalia: Thalia and the Cristina Show scored major Tv ratings !!! |website=Thalia3arabia.blogspot.com |date=2 August 2008 |access-date=27 August 2016}}</ref>

"[[Será porque te amo]]", the second single, received no promotion and became another failed single. It is a Spanish language cover version of the Italian hit "Sarà perché ti amo", originally performed by the group [[Ricchi e Poveri]].

On 23 October, it was announced that Thalía was suffering from [[Lyme disease]], which is transmitted by ticks. Fortunately, it was discovered quickly, and the singer, as well as her mother, Yolanda Miranda, were able to receive antibiotics in time.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.peopleenespanol.com/pespanol/en/articles/0,22490,1853205,00.html |title=Thalía is suffering from Lyme disease |language=es |website=PeopleenEspanol.com |date=23 October 2008 |access-date=27 August 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100413085635/http://www.peopleenespanol.com/pespanol/en/articles/0,22490,1853205,00.html |archive-date=13 April 2010 |url-status=dead  }}</ref> On 18 November, Thalía announced the end of her collaboration with [[EMI Music]].

Despite Lunada being a commercial disappointment, it was named as the "Best Album of the Year" by [[¡Hola!]] readers.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hola.com/musica/2008/12/13/mejor-disco-2008/ |title='Lunada', de Thalía, Elegido Mejor Disco de 2008 Por Nuestros Internautas |access-date=15 December 2008 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081216151508/http://www.hola.com/musica/2008/12/13/mejor-disco-2008/ |archive-date=16 December 2008}}</ref> The latest work of the Mexican singer achieved 8,750 votes beating artists, such as [[Luis Miguel]], [[Britney Spears]], [[Mariah Carey]], [[Beyoncé Knowles|Beyoncé]] and [[Madonna]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://nuestrathalia.com/2008/12/15/lunada-named-as-best-album-of-the-year-by-hola-readers/|title='Lunada' named as Best Album of the Year by Hola readers|website=Nuestrathalia.com|access-date=27 August 2016|url-status=bot: unknown|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081216154307/http://nuestrathalia.com/2008/12/15/lunada-named-as-best-album-of-the-year-by-hola-readers/|archive-date=16 December 2008}}</ref>

===2009–2011: Success of ''Primera Fila'' and ''Growing Stronger''===
On 30 July 2009, Thalía recorded her [[Acoustic music|acoustic]] album, ''[[Primera fila (Thalía album)|Primera fila]]'', her first album after she signed with [[Sony Music Entertainment]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.eluniversal.com.mx/espectaculos/92275.html|title=El Universal – El regreso de Thalia será en acústico|date=21 June 2013|website=Eluniversal.com.mx|access-date=31 October 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.peopleenespanol.com/article/thalia-firma-con-sony-bmg-grabara-disco-acustico-en-vivo|title=Thalía firma con Sony-BMG; grabará disco acústico en vivo|work=PeopleenEspanol.com|access-date=31 October 2014}}</ref> In October, Thalía performed at the [[White House]], along with other Latin singers, in an event organized by President [[Barack Obama]] that celebrated [[Hispanic]] heritage. Thalía's performance was iconic and historic, as she was the first celebrity to publicly invite a United States President to dance.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.terra.com.mx/musica/articulo/877798/Obama+baila+con+Thalia+en+Fiesta+Latina+de+la+Casa+Blanca.htm|title=Obama baila con Thalía en Fiesta Latina de la Casa Blanca|work=Terra|access-date=31 October 2014|archive-date=12 April 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130412045150/http://www.terra.com.mx/musica/articulo/877798/Obama+baila+con+Thalia+en+Fiesta+Latina+de+la+Casa+Blanca.htm|url-status=dead}}</ref>

In October of the same year, she released the first single from ''Primera fila'', a song named [[Equivocada]]. In December Thalía released her album, which contained duets with [[Joan Sebastian]] and [[Pedro Capó]] and various other songs, that became huge radio hits in the following months. The production received critical accept and very positive reviews, while Jason Birchmeier stated that "Primera Fila" was one of the best albums Thalía has released in her whole career, and definitely the one with the most surprises.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/thalia-en-primera-fila-sony-music-mw0001326602|title=Primera Fila – Thalía – Songs, Reviews, Credits, Awards – AllMusic|first=Jason|last=Birchmeier|work=AllMusic|access-date=31 October 2014}}</ref> As for Thalía, she considered [[Primera Fila (Thalía album)|Primera Fila]] as "the most personal album" in her career.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.google.com/hostednews/epa/article/ALeqM5gRe6j2uCy1-sAbFPbkG6ZDsbqWyA|archive-url=https://archive.today/20130103025227/http://www.google.com/hostednews/epa/article/ALeqM5gRe6j2uCy1-sAbFPbkG6ZDsbqWyA|url-status=dead|title=epa – european pressphoto agency: Thalía afirma que si muriera mañana...|date=3 January 2013|archive-date=3 January 2013}}</ref>

Regarding to the album's commercial performance, ''Primera fila'' received diamond and triple platinum sales certifications in Mexico, where it was announced by the end of 2011 that the album had sold over 500,000 copies according to [[Asociación Mexicana de Productores de Fonogramas y Videogramas|AMPROFON]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.informador.com.mx/entretenimiento/2010/221942/6/thalia-celebra-el-primer-aniversario-de-su-primera-fila.htm|title=Thalía celebra el primer aniversario de su ''Primera fila''|work=EL INFORMADOR|access-date=31 October 2014}}</ref> ''Primera fila'' was the best selling album in Mexico in 2010, where it topped the charts for 55 non-consecutive weeks, the most weeks ever in Mexico's recorded music chart history.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.vanguardia.com.mx/primerafilaeldiscomasvendidoelanodethalia-619938.html |title='Primera Fila, el disco más vendido: El año de ThalÃa |website=Vanguardia.com.mx |access-date=31 October 2014 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141220232606/http://www.vanguardia.com.mx/primerafilaeldiscomasvendidoelanodethalia-619938.html |archive-date=20 December 2014}}</ref> In [[Greece]] and Spain, the album reached the positions No. 6 and No. 32, respectively, while it reached No. 4 in ''[[Billboard Magazine|Billboard's]]'' top Latin Albums<ref name="billboard.com">{{cite magazine|url=http://www.billboard.com/charts/2009-12-19/latin-albums|title=Top Latin Albums|date=19 December 2012|magazine=Billboard|access-date=31 October 2014}}</ref><ref name="ReferenceA">{{cite magazine|url=http://www.billboard.com/charts/2010-10-23/latin-pop-albums|title=Latin Pop Albums|date=19 December 2012|magazine=Billboard|access-date=31 October 2014}}</ref> and No. 2 in Billboard's Latin Pop Albums<ref name="ReferenceA"/><ref>{{cite magazine|url=http://www.billboard.com/charts/2009-12-19/latin-pop-albums|title=Latin Pop Albums|date=19 December 2012|magazine=Billboard|access-date=31 October 2014}}</ref> charts. Initially, ''Primera Fila'' had reached No. 1 on both aforementioned charts, but sales of the standard edition and the Walmart edition were later divided, leading to a retraction and update to Billboard's official peak positions for ''Primera Fila''. After these changes, ''Primera fila'' went from a peak position of No. 167 to a peak position of No. 198 on the [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' 200]] albums chart.<ref name="billboard.com"/> Until the month of October 2012, ''Primera fila'' had sold over 1.5&nbsp;million copies worldwide.<ref>{{cite web|author=Washington, NJ (Ubicación actual) |url=http://mx.noticias.yahoo.com/disco-thalia-hab%C3%ADtame-%C3%ADntimo-cargado-sentimientos-212230030.html |archive-url=https://archive.today/20121209080249/http://mx.noticias.yahoo.com/disco-thalia-hab%C3%ADtame-%C3%ADntimo-cargado-sentimientos-212230030.html |url-status=dead |archive-date=9 December 2012 |title=Yahoo |website=Mx.noticias.yahoo.com |date=28 October 2010 |access-date=27 August 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.impremedia.com/article/20121016/IMPORT01/310169970 |title=Thalía regresa con 'Habítame siempre' |date=16 October 2012 |website=Impremedia.com |access-date=31 October 2014 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141006135203/http://www.impremedia.com/article/20121016/IMPORT01/310169970 |archive-date=6 October 2014}}</ref>

In September 2010, Thalía released a special anniversary edition of the album under the title ''Primera fila... Un año después'', which included 8 songs from the original album, as well as 2 never-released before songs, 2 remixes and a DVD with a documentary of the recording process of the album. In October 2010, [[Michael Bublé]] invited her to record a song with him in his holiday album ''[[Christmas (Michael Bublé album)|Christmas]]''. Together they recorded the bilingual song "Mis Deseos/Feliz Navidad" and their collaboration received very positive reviews. <!--<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/christmas-mw0001449190|title=Christmas – Michael Bublé – Songs, Reviews, Credits, Awards|first=Matt|last=Collar|work=AllMusic|access-date=31 October 2014}}</ref> Need a new ref; fact not mentioned in this citation-->

===2012–2013: ''Habitame Siempre'' and ''VIVA! Tour''===
Thalía had a collaboration with US music veteran [[Tony Bennett]] for his "Viva:Duets" album, which was released on 22 October 2012. Together they performed live the classic song "The way you look tonight" in Today's show and the [[Katie Couric]]'s show.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://nbclatino.com/2012/10/23/thalia-makes-today-show-appearance-with-stellar-tony-bennett-duet/|website=Nbclatino.com| title=Thalia makes Today Show appearance with stellar Tony Bennett duet|first=Nina|last=Terrero| date=23 October 2012}}</ref>

During the past months, she had announced that she was recording her eleventh studio album, ''[[Habítame siempre]]''. On 21 September 2012, Thalía gave a private concert in New York City at [[Hammerstein Ballroom]] as a preview of the upcoming album. The album's lead single, "[[Manías]]", was released on 8 October 2012.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.filmeweb.net/magazine.asp?id=8895|title=Thalía shows her new "Manias"|work=Filmeweb.net|date=13 October 2012|access-date=15 October 2012|language=es|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130412030258/http://www.filmeweb.net/magazine.asp?id=8895|archive-date=12 April 2013}}</ref> ''Habítame siempre'' was released on 19 November 2012, in the United States and Latin America under the label of [[Sony Music Latin]], while in Europe it is set to be released in 2013 by [[Sony BMG|BMG Music]]. The album contains collaborations with [[Robbie Williams]], [[Michael Bublé]], [[Prince Royce]] and [[Gilberto Santa Rosa]], among others and immensely after its release, it received mostly positive reviews. ''Habitame Siempre'' was certified [[platinum certification|triple platinum]] plus [[gold certification|gold]] in Mexico for sales of more than 210,000 copies, [[gold certification|gold]] in the United States for shipments exceeding 50,000 copies and [[platinum certification|platinum]] in Venezuela for over 10,000 copies shipped.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.elentrerios.com/index.php/entretenimiento/music/39087-thalia-numero-uno-en-ventas-en-estados-unidos-|title=Muerte en el Parque Industrial |author=Advertis Web Factory|date=30 October 2014|website=Elentereios.com|access-date=31 October 2014}}</ref> In the meantime the second single of the album, "[[Te Perdiste Mi Amor]]", was certified [[platinum certification|platinum]] in Mexico for digital sales of over 60,000 copies.

On 24 March 2013, Thalía launched her [[The VIVA! Tour|VIVA! Tour]] in support of [[Habítame Siempre]]. [[The VIVA! Tour]] marks Thalía's first tour in a decade and consists of a series of intimate concerts in the United States and Mexico. Thalía stated in an interview that she also plans to expand the tour to Latin America, Europe and Asia if it meets positive commercial reception.

In October 2013, Thalía released in the United States and Latin America her fourth book ''Chupie (The Binky That Returned Home)'', and on 12 November, Thalía released in Mexico her second live album ''VIVA! Tour''. This album was recorded on 27 April 2013, during her concert in Mexico City. In United States and Latin America, the album was released on 1 December 2013. It was certified [[gold certification|gold]] in Mexico on its second week on the market for sales exceeding 30,000 copies.

On 5 December 2013, she received her own star in the [[Hollywood Walk of Fame]] as a recognition of her success.<ref name="abullseyeview">{{cite news| url=http://abullseyeview.com/playlist-target-interview-thalia-queen-latin-pop/| work=A Bullseye View| title=[PLAYLIST] A Q&A with the Queen of Latin Pop| date=15 November 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121121025604/http://abullseyeview.com/playlist-target-interview-thalia-queen-latin-pop/|archive-date=21 November 2012|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref name="Hernandez">{{cite news| url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2012/06/26/thalia-hollywood-walk-of-fame_n_1628329.html | work=Huffington Post | first=Lee | last=Hernandez | title=Thalía To Get Star On Hollywood Walk Of Fame | date=26 June 2012}}</ref>

===2014–2015: ''Viva Kids'' and ''Amore Mio''===
On 25 March 2014, Thalía released her first children album ''[[Viva Kids Vol. 1]]'' in Mexico. The album contains 11 songs and received one nomination to Latin Grammy Awards 2014.
''Vamos A Jugar'' was the first single of the album and was released on 18 March 2014. ''Viva Kids Vol. 1'' was released in US, on 5 June 2014.

On 22 July 2014, Italian singer [[Laura Pausini]] confirmed that by September that same year she would release a special version of her [[20 – The Greatest Hits (Laura Pausini album)|greatest hits album]] to the Hispanophone market, in an edition containing new duet with Thalía in ''[[Se non te|Sino a ti]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tgcom24.mediaset.it/televisione/2014/notizia/laura-pausini-sara-coach-a-la-voz-mexico-_2058857.shtml |publisher=TGcom24 |title=Laura Pausini sarà coach a La voz... México |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141020081108/http://www.tgcom24.mediaset.it/televisione/2014/notizia/laura-pausini-sara-coach-a-la-voz-mexico-_2058857.shtml |archive-date=20 October 2014}}</ref>

On 9 September 2014, Thalía released the lead single of ''[[Amore Mio (Thalía album)|Amore Mio]]'', "[[Por Lo Que Reste De Vida]]". The song debuted No. 50 in the ''Billboard'' [[Hot Latin Songs]] chart. The video music was released on 14 October 2014.

Thalía released her 12th studio album on 17 November 2014. ''Amore Mio'' was Thalía's second album that debuted at No. 1 on the ''Billboard'' Top Latin Albums chart. The album debuted at No. 173 on the [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' 200]] with 3,000 copies sold in first week in the US. In Mexico, the album debuted at No. 1. In December 2014, to celebrate Thalía's 25th anniversary as a solo artist, her first three albums were released as a digital download from [[iTunes]] and [[Spotify]].

In January 2015, Thalía released her first fashion collection in United States with [[Macy's]].

===2016–2017: ''Latina'', world tour, and directorial debut===
On 26 February 2016, she revealed through her social media accounts the album cover for her then-upcoming studio album, ''[[Latina (album)|Latina]]'', which was released on 21 April 2016. The album's first single, "[[Desde Esa Noche]]" featuring [[Maluma (singer)|Maluma]], peaked at number 16 on the Hot Latin Songs chart and number 4 on the Latin Pop Airplay chart. The second single of the album, [[Vuélveme a Querer (Thalía song)|Vuélveme a Querer]] was released on 29 April 2016. The third single of album was [[Todavía Te Quiero]] featuring [[De La Ghetto]] was released on 2 December 2016.

Thalía has announced she will embark on a new tour, her third overall, called [[Latina Love Tour]].

In 2017 she made her directorial debut when she co-directed "15: A Quinceañera Story", a four-part series of documentary shorts that follows five latina quinceañeras.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.hbo.com/documentaries/15-a-quinceanera-story-ashley/15-a-quinceanera-story-documentary-premiere|title=15: A Quinceañera Story: Ashley – 15: A Quinceañera Story Documentary Premiere|website=HBO}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thecut.com/2017/12/interview-zoey-luna-trans-teen-in-15-a-quinceanera-story.html|title=How a Trans Teen Got Her Quinceañera|first=Jada|last=Yuan|date=29 December 2017|website=The Cut}}</ref> For this she received a nomination for Outstanding Directorial Achievement in Children's Programs at the [[70th Directors Guild of America Awards]]<ref>{{cite web|title=DGA Announces Nominees for Outstanding Directorial Achievement in Television, Commercials and Documentary for 2017|url=https://www.dga.org/News/PressReleases/2018/180110-70th-Annual-DGA-Awards-Television-Commercial-and-Documentary-Nominees-Announced.aspx|publisher=[[Directors Guild of America]]|date=10 January 2018|access-date=10 January 2018}}</ref> That same year she collaborated with Colombian singer [[Carlos Vives]] in the song "Todo Me Gusta" from his album "Vives". The song was not released as a single but still managed to peak at number 12 in Bolivia and also peaked at number 14 the U.S. Tropical Digital Songs Chart.<ref name=BoliviaChart>{{cite web
 |url=http://charts.monitorlatino.com/top20/Print/bolivia/general/20171218
 |work=[[Monitor Latino]]
 |access-date=18 December 2017 |title=Bolivia Charts – Monitor Latino 
 }}</ref><ref name="ThaliaJDSS">{{cite magazine|url=https://www.billboard.com/music/thalia/chart-history/jazz-digital-song-sales |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190810212616/https://www.billboard.com/music/thalia/chart-history/jazz-digital-song-sales |url-status=dead |archive-date=10 August 2019 |title=Thalia Jazz Digital Song Sales|magazine=Billboard |date=8 February 2020 |access-date=3 February 2020}}</ref>

===2018–2019:  Donna Summer Musical, Eyelure, ''Valiente'', and Adria===
In 2018 she produced [[Summer: The Donna Summer Musical]] on [[Broadway theatre|Broadway]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.hoyestado.com/2018/04/thalia-produce-musical-de-donna-summer/|title=Thalía produce musical de Donna Summer|date=24 April 2018}}</ref> The musical is based on the life of [[Donna Summer]].

In August 2018 she released her false eyelash and eyebrow collection called ''Eyelure'' which is available at [[Walmart]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.usmagazine.com/stylish/news/thalia-sodis-tips-for-her-eylure-false-eyelash-and-eyebrow-collection/|title=Thalia Tells Us the Surprising Reason She Always Wears False Eyelashes|date=20 August 2018}}</ref>

Thalía released her fourteenth studio album, [[Valiente (album)|Valiente]], on 9 November 2018. The lead single [[No Me Acuerdo]] was certified quadruple platinum in both Mexico and the United States as well as double platinum in Spain. The album also spawned the hits [[Me Oyen, Me Escuchan]], [[Lento (Thalía song)|Lento]], and [[Lindo Pero Bruto]] with the latter being certified gold in the United States. The album had a total of 8 songs released as singles.

In January 2019 she released her line of hair care products called Adria by Thalía.<ref>[https://www.adriabythalia.com/ Adria by Thalía]</ref> The 7 piece collection in available in stores at [[Walmart]] and [[Target Corporation|Target]] as well as online.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.prnewswire.com/news-releases/the-thalia-sodi-brand-launches-new-hair-care-line-adria-by-thalia-300783321.html|title=The Thalia Sodi Brand Launches New Hair Care Line, Adria By Thalia|website=prnewswire.com}}</ref>

===2020–present: New collaborations, ''Viva Kids 2'', and ''DesAMORfosis''===
In January 2020 Thalía released the single "[[Ya Tú Me Conoces]]" with Venezuelan brother duo [[Mau y Ricky]].<ref>[https://revoluciontrespuntocero.mx/thalia-estrena-ya-tu-me-conoces-junto-a-mau-y-ricky-logran-debutar-en-22-paises-como-turquia-rumania-grecia-y-hungria-video/ Thalía estrena "Ya Tu Me Conoces" junto a Mau y Ricky, logran debutar en 22 países como Turquía, Rumania, Grecia y Hungría #VIDEO] Consultado el 26 de enero de 2020</ref> The song served as the lead single from her 17th studio album. A month after that she collaborated with Mexican duo [[Rio Roma]] on their song "[[Lo Siento Mucho]]", which entered the top 10 on the Mexican charts. A month later she collaborated again, this time with Brazilian drag queen [[Pabllo Vittar]] on the song "[[Tímida]]", which served as the fifth single for his album ''[[111 (Pabllo Vittar album)|111]]''.

In May 2020, the magazine ''[[People en Español]]'' named her the number-one most influential Mexican star of all time for her success as a singer, actress, and entrepreneur.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://peopleenespanol.com/noticias/los-10-mexicanos-mas-influyentes-en-el-mundo-del-entretenimiento/|title=Los 10 mexicanos más influyentes en el mundo del entretenimiento|website=People en Español}}</ref> Later that month, she released her second children's album titled [[Viva Kids Vol. 2]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://crnnoticias.com/thalia-lanza-album-viva-kids-vol-2/|title=Thalía lanza álbum "Viva Kids Vol. 2"|date=1 June 2020}}</ref>

In June 2020 she collaborated with Peruvian singer [[Leslie Shaw]] on her single "[[Estoy Soltera]]", which also features Colombian singer [[Farina (singer)|Farina]] and served as the third single from Shaw's EP [[Yo Soy Leslie Shaw]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://rpp.pe/musica/nacional/leslie-shaw-y-thalia-estrenan-estoy-soltera-nuevo-tema-junto-a-farina-noticia-1274302|title=[VIDEO] Leslie Shaw y Thalía estrenan "Estoy Soltera", nuevo tema junto a Farina|date=19 June 2020|website=RPP}}</ref>

She released the second single of her upcoming studio album titled "[[La Luz (Thalía song)|La Luz]]" on 28 August 2020, on which she collaborated with Puerto Rican rapper [[Myke Towers]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.elnuevodia.com/entretenimiento/musica/notas/thalia-lanza-tema-con-myke-towers/|title=Thalía lanza tema con Myke Towers|date=29 August 2020|website=El Nuevo Día}}</ref> A month later she started on a Facebook watch series called '''''Latin Music Queens''''' alongside [[Sofía Reyes]] and Farina. The series would lead up to the release of two more singles with the first one being [[Ten Cuidao]] with [[Farina (singer)|Farina]] which premiered on episode three<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sonymusiclatin.com/farina-thalia-lanzan-su-sencillo-y-video-ten-cuidao/|title=FARINA & THALIA lanzan su sencillo y video "TEN CUIDAO"|date=8 October 2020|website=Sony Music Entertainment Latin}}</ref> and the second single being [[Tick Tock (Thalía, Farina, and Sofía Reyes song)|Tick Tock]] which featured all three singers and premiered after the sixth and final episode.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://wowlarevista.com/thalia-sofia-reyes-farina-lanza-su-nuevo-tema-tick-tock/|title=THALIA + SOFÍA REYES + FARINA lanza su nuevo tema "Tick Tock" {{pipe}} Wow La Revista|first=Bolivar|last=Feijoo|website=wowlarevista.com|date=31 October 2020}}</ref> The latter also served as the third single from Thalía's upcoming album.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.gq.com.mx/entretenimiento/articulo/thalia-en-entrevista-sobre-triunfar-en-tiktok-y-nuevas-canciones|title=Thalia: "Necesitaba compartir canciones en la pandemia para estar cuerda"|website=GQ Mexico|date=13 November 2020}}</ref>

On 7 May 2021 she released [[Mojito (song)|Mojito]] which served as the fourth single from her album [[Desamorfosis|DesAMORfosis]] which she released on 14 May 2021.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://los40.cl/2021/la-oyen-la-escuchan-thalia-lanzara-nuevo-disco-y-estamos-en-llamas-76687.html|title=¡La oyen, la escuchan! Thalía lanzará nuevo disco y estamos en llamas|work=[[Los 40]]|date=4 May 2021|access-date=26 May 2021|first=Joce |last=Acuña|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210513032147/https://los40.cl/2021/la-oyen-la-escuchan-thalia-lanzara-nuevo-disco-y-estamos-en-llamas-76687.html|archive-date=13 May 2021|url-status=live}}</ref>

==Acting career==
Thalia was cast in a supporting role in the 1986 [[telenovela]] ''[[Pobre señorita Limantour]]'' with which she began her collaboration with [[Televisa]], the largest mass media company in the Spanish-speaking world. In 1987, she went on to star in her first major role for Televisa in the 1987 teenage drama series ''[[Quinceañera (telenovela)|Quinceañera]]'', along with Mexican actress [[Adela Noriega]]. ''Quinceañera'' won the ''TV y Novelas'' award for Best Telenovela of the Year 1988. In 1989, she got her first lead role in ''Luz y Sombra'', which was less successful.

In 1992, Thalía shot to fame starring in ''[[María Mercedes (Mexican TV series)|María Mercedes]]'', for which she won a TV Y Novelas Award for Best Young Actress in 1993. This series was her first of three telenovelas later called ''Las Tres Marias'' ("The Three Marías") for sharing the character name. ''[[Marimar (Mexican telenovela)|Marimar]]'' began in 1994 and ''[[Maria la del Barrio]]'' in 1995. The third was the most commercially successful of her career and it remains her most iconic role, while ''Marimar'' is considered by some critics the best telenovela of all time.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.buzzfeed.com/briangalindo/ranking-the-5-best-telenovela-roles-of-thalia#36s5riv|title=Ranking The 5 Best Telenovela Roles Of Thalía|publisher=[[BuzzFeed]]|access-date=20 October 2014|date=15 January 2014|first=Brian|last=Galindo}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.latinpost.com/articles/6284/20140123/latin-post-exclusive-6-telenovelas-cant-forget.htm|title=6 Best Telenovelas of All Time: Marimar, El Clon, and More|publisher=Latin Post|access-date=20 October 2014|date=23 January 2014|first=Solmarie|last=Santiago}}</ref> In 1999, Thalía starred in her last telenovela, "[[Rosalinda (telenovela)|Rosalinda]]". All four telenovelas were basically based on the same rags to riches character.<ref name="tevnovelas.blogspot.gr">{{cite web|url=http://tevnovelas.blogspot.gr/2011/07/thalia-legendary-telenovela-actresses.html|title=Thalia a Legendary Telenovela actresses|website=Tevnovelas.blogspot.gr|access-date=31 October 2014|archive-date=11 April 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130411200946/http://tevnovelas.blogspot.gr/2011/07/thalia-legendary-telenovela-actresses.html|url-status=dead}}</ref>
With these telenovelas, Thalía became famous worldwide because of the extremely high ratings they achieved in more than 180 countries (especially the [[Philippines]]).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sunstar.com.ph//article/403886|title=What's the latest with Thalia?|last=Molbog-Mendoza|first=Jenny|date=9 November 2017|website=Sunstar|language=en|access-date=31 October 2019}}</ref>

Although Thalía's presence in television is legendary, her presence in [[Filmmaking|cinema]] is less important. She appeared for the first time in a movie when she was still a child in the 1979 film "La Guerra De los Pasteles" ("The War of the Cakes"). Furthermore, in 1999, she starred in ''"Mambo Café"'', a modest [[independent film|indie]] film production that had a poor reception from critics.

===Cultural impact of telenovelas===
Thalía has been labeled by various mass media companies as the "queen of soap operas",<ref name="delafont">{{cite web|url=http://delafont.com/music_acts/thalia.htm|title=THALIA booking – Latin Music Artists – Corporate Event Booking Agent|website=Delafont.com|access-date=31 October 2014}}</ref> because her presence in television during the decade of the '90s was phenomenal. She became one of the world's foremost and most enduring television personalities as she starred in Mexico's highest-rated telenovelas ever that were exported in over 180 countries and viewed by about 2&nbsp;billion people. It is stated by international media experts that at some point at the midst of the telenovela craze, Thalía's name even became synonymous with her native country, Mexico.

According to the newspaper ''Ivoir'Soir'': "At 7.30 sharp in the evening, when Marimar comes on, everything stops in Côte d'Ivoire". It is also mentioned that "Marimar" could attract more local fans than the 1998 World Cup, and that the program arrived in Africa after being a phenomenal rating hit in Indonesia and the Philippines, where in 1997 she was received in [[Manila]] like a foreign [[head of state]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.questia.com/library/1G1-54738757/soaps-with-a-latin-scent |title="Soaps with a Latin Scent" by Ortiz de Urbina, Araceli; Lopez, Asbel – UNESCO Courier, May 1999 |date=12 April 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130412032456/https://www.questia.com/library/1G1-54738757/soaps-with-a-latin-scent |archive-date=12 April 2013 |url-status=dead}}</ref>

Thalía stated in her autobiography regarding to the impact of her telenovelas: "Soap operas made a lot of history; just look at the report by UNESCO, where it was noted that "in the [[Ivory Coast]] in Africa and in Paris (France), people stopped the daily course of their lives just to watch a soap opera. I never expected that kind of success [...] Whenever I arrived anywhere, I was treated like royalty; even the press in some of these countries referred to me as the Aztec Queen, the Mexican Queen, or the ambassador of Mexico, and like a proud peacock, I always brought my country's flag with me wherever I went to represent my motherland. I was in the clouds at the pinnacle of my career [...] During my visit at the Philippines, the organizers informed me that the last time so many people gathered in the streets for a person was when [[Pope John Paul II|Pope John Paul the Second]] came to visit on January fourteenth, 1995 [...] In the Philippines, the country that probably felt the greatest impact from Marimar, the show was more widely promoted than the 1998 World Cup and more highly rated than the Super Bowl or the Grammys. In fact while I was visiting the country, the people and the media were so enthralled to see [[Marimar (Mexican telenovela)|Marimar]] in the flesh that a historic peace treaty between the government and the guerillas and the centennial celebrations of the [[Philippine Revolution]]s that were happening at the same time were pushed aside in the midst of Marimar fever. As a result, the archipelago was temporarily dubbed "República de MariMar."

The phenomenon of Thalía's telenovelas also became visible in countries like [[Brazil]], [[Bulgaria]], [[Libya]], [[Egypt]], [[France]], [[Greece]], [[Hungary]], [[Indonesia]], [[Lebanon]], [[Poland]], [[Portugal]], [[Romania]], [[Russia]], [[Syria]], [[Turkey]] and the majority of Spanish-speaking countries around the world.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pep.ph/spotlight/looking-back/13166/The-Marimar-Craze|title=The "Marimar" Craze|first=Michael|last=Ancheta|date=19 July 2007|website=Pep.ph|access-date=31 October 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141031024640/http://www.pep.ph/spotlight/looking-back/13166/The-Marimar-Craze|archive-date=31 October 2014}}</ref>

==Business endeavours==
[[File:ThaliaVisionExpo2007.jpg|thumb|Thalía in a Visión Expo event in 2007, presenting her eyewear collections]]

Her first business endeavour started with a women's underwear line in 1993, and launched in 1995. It become a success in her native country.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.diezminutos.es/telenovela/g38050243/thalia-vida-edad-canciones/|title=La vida y canciones de Thalía en imágenes|first=Vilma|last=Degorgue Alegre|work=[[Diez Minutos]]|access-date=14 March 2022|language=es|date=24 December 2021}}</ref> In 2002, Thalía signed a deal with [[Kmart Corporation|Kmart]] to release her own clothing collection for women, as well as accessories and home products. In the middle of 2003, the "Thalía Sodi" collection was officially available in the US market in over 2,000 stores. Thalía commented: "My collection is a dream come true. I'm so happy to have created a clothing line inspired by my culture, trying to show the colors and the passion of our culture, that captures also a big part of my personal style". Thalía became the first Mexican woman to launch a clothing brand in the US.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.elsiglodetorreon.com.mx/noticia/43573.thalia-esta-a-la-venta.html|title=Thalía está a la venta|date=8 August 2003|access-date=31 October 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.bizjournals.com/southflorida/stories/2003/08/04/daily28.html | title=Kmart launches Thalia Sodi Collection in Miami}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://famosos.about.com/od/tuscantantesfavoritos/p/Pefil-De-Thal-Ia.htm|title=Thalía – Perfil de Thalía|first=Madelyn|last=Rodriguez|work=About|access-date=31 October 2014|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130114155204/http://famosos.about.com/od/tuscantantesfavoritos/p/Pefil-De-Thal-Ia.htm|archive-date=14 January 2013}}</ref>

Simultaneously, Thalía debuted her eyewear collection under the brand name "Thalía Eyewear Collection" in association with Kenmark Optical.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://musica.univision.com/noticias/article/2002-04-21/thalia-mira-al-futuro-con|title=Ultimas Noticias de Música Latina e Internacional – Univision Música|work=Univision.com|access-date=31 October 2014}}</ref> In 2005, the line also became available in Mexico's market as Thalía signed a deal with "Devlyn" company.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.elmanana.com.mx/notas.asp?id%3D53859 |title=El Mañana &#124; Revista &#124; ¿Crean sus productos? |access-date=15 November 2012 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080501115410/http://www.elmanana.com.mx/notas.asp?id=53859 |archive-date=1 May 2008}}</ref> Up to 2007, Thalía had generated US$100&nbsp;million from the sales of "Thalía Eyewear", with more than 1 million products sold.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www2.esmas.com/ritmoson-latino/artistas/054422/thalia?country_code=US|title=Ritmoson|access-date=31 October 2014}}</ref> Precisely in 2007 Thalía presented a new eyewear collection in New York, and the brand was exported to over eighty countries around the world.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.terra.com.mx/entretenimiento/articulo/156121/Thalia+presento+su+nueva+linea+de+lentes.htm|title=Terra – Thalía presentó su nueva línea de lentes – Famosos – Gente E|access-date=31 October 2014|archive-date=13 October 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121013125109/http://www.terra.com.mx/entretenimiento/articulo/156121/Thalia+presento+su+nueva+linea+de+lentes.htm|url-status=dead}}</ref>

[[File:Thalia girl.gif|thumb|left|Thalia logo used in many of her business ventures]]

In April 2004, she entered the editorial market by releasing her own magazine ''Thalía'' in US, produced by American Media and oriented to the female Latin youth. The magazine included consultation and reports about issues like health, fashion and beauty.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.writenews.com/2004/043004_ami_thalia.htm|title=American Media's Thalia Magazine Premieres|work=The Write News|access-date=31 October 2014}}</ref> Some months later, in September, Thalía became the face of jewels' company Jacob & Co.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.jacobandco.com/thalia04a.pdf |title=Singing Superstar Thalia signs on as the first face of JACOB & Co. |access-date=27 August 2016 |url-status=bot: unknown |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081001214807/http://www.jacobandco.com/thalia04a.pdf |archive-date=1 October 2008}}</ref>

In 2004, she signed a contract with [[The Hershey Company|Hershey's]] with which she released her own chocolate and candy brand.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://stilo.es/contenido/noticias/2004/0404/1404/noticias_stilo-140404/noticias_stilo-140404-9.htm|title=La cantante mexicana Thalia será marca de chocolate en EEUU|access-date=31 October 2014|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141031042033/http://stilo.es/contenido/noticias/2004/0404/1404/noticias_stilo-140404/noticias_stilo-140404-9.htm|archive-date=31 October 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hersheys.com.mx/03Promociones/thalia/productos.html |title=--HERSHey's México-- |access-date=15 November 2012 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111203115502/http://www.hersheys.com.mx/03Promociones/thalia/productos.html |archive-date=3 December 2011}}</ref> In 2005, she designed a summer clothing line,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.terra.com/mujer/articulo/html/hof20159.htm|title=Thalia lanza su coleccion para la temporada de verano – terra|access-date=31 October 2014}}</ref> and in the following year, she was converted into the face of "Carol's Daughter" company, specialized in beauty products,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ahorroslarevista.com/2011/08/exitosa-thalia/ |title=Exitosa Thalía &#124; Ahorros LA Revista |access-date=15 November 2012 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131029192810/http://www.ahorroslarevista.com/2011/08/exitosa-thalia/ |archive-date=29 October 2013}}</ref> while in 2007 she launched her perfume, produced by "Fuller Cosmetics" company.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://elmanana.com.mx/notas.asp?id%3D26733 |title=Lanza Thalía su perfume - el Mañana - Revista |access-date=15 November 2012 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120307065337/http://elmanana.com.mx/notas.asp?id=26733 |archive-date=7 March 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.elmanana.com.mx/notas.asp?id%3D32003 |title=El Mañana &#124; Revista &#124; Thalía diseña camisetas |access-date=15 November 2012 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071221063638/http://www.elmanana.com.mx/notas.asp?id=32003 |archive-date=21 December 2007}}</ref> In 2007, she joined ABC Radio and started her own radio show known as "The Conexión Thalía Radio Show", in which she discusses music, fashion, news and political issues, and invites various people to talk with her on different issues.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://abcradionetworks.com/Article.asp?id=416838 |title=Home – ABC Radio |website=Abcradionetworks.com |date=20 June 2014 |access-date=27 August 2016}}</ref> The program, that is weekly and lasts two hours, premiered on 17 March 2007, and still goes on, while it has expanded to over 70 radio stations through the US.

In September 2007, she released the beauty advice book "Thalía: ¡Belleza!-Lessons in Lipgloss and Happiness"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.chroniclebooks.com/index/main,book-info/store,books/products_id,6716/ |title=Thalia: ?Belleza!: Lessons in Lipgloss and Happiness $19.95 : Chronicle Books |access-date=27 September 2008 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081013141357/http://www.chroniclebooks.com/index/main%2Cbook-info/store%2Cbooks/products_id%2C6716/ |archive-date=13 October 2008}}</ref> and in June 2009, she released her second book entitled "Thalia: ¡Radiante!-Your Guide to a Fit and a Fabulous Pregnancy". In May 2010, she revealed new accessories and jewels available via her website, apart from a new clothing line in association with multinational company [[C&A]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://impreso.elnuevodiario.com.ni/2010/05/11/variedades/124062 |title=El Nuevo Diario • Noticias de Nicaragua, Centroamérica y el Mundo |website=Impreso.elnuevodiario.com.ni |access-date=27 August 2016 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131029193501/http://impreso.elnuevodiario.com.ni/2010/05/11/variedades/124062 |archive-date=29 October 2013}}</ref> In February 2011, she became the new face of [[Head & Shoulders]] and in November, she released her third book, which is her autobiography and named "Growing Stronger".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.merca20.com/thalia-nueva-imagen-de-head-shoulders/|title=Thalia, nueva imagen de Head & Shoulders|work=Revista Merca2.0|date=25 February 2011|access-date=31 October 2014}}</ref> Thalía has also been the public face of various advertisements, like [[Dr Pepper]] in 2001 or [[Victoria's Secret]] in 2005. According to ''Mira!'' magazine, in 2008 it was estimated that Thalía was one of the most wealthy Mexican businesswomen with a net worth of over US$100&nbsp;million.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://sonfamosos.com/2008/02/28/thalia-es-la-mas-rica-de-mexico-con-100-millones-de-dolares/|title=Thalía es la más rica de México con 100 millones de dólares|work=Son Famosos|access-date=31 October 2014|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141031062939/http://sonfamosos.com/2008/02/28/thalia-es-la-mas-rica-de-mexico-con-100-millones-de-dolares/|archive-date=31 October 2014}}</ref> In April 2012, she inaugurated her own yoga center in New York.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://entretenimiento.terra.com.mx/famosos/thalia-abre-centro-de-yoga-en-nueva-york,1456675b946c6310VgnVCM5000009ccceb0aRCRD.html|title=Thalía inaugura su centro de yoga en Nueva York|first=Elia|last=Fless|work=Terra|access-date=31 October 2014}}</ref>

In 2015, she signed a contract with "ePura", a Mexican water company and she also signed an exclusive deal with [[Macy's]] to launch her apparel, shoes and jewelry collections. Jeffrey Gennette, [[Macy's]] president stated that "the ''Thalia Sodi'' collection is the biggest private-brand launch in the history of the company by a long shot."<ref>{{cite web|first=David |last=Moin |url=http://wwd.com/globe-news/people/macys-latin-turn-with-thalia-8122155/ |title=Macy's Latin Turn With Thalia – WWD |website=Wwd.com |date=20 January 2015 |access-date=27 August 2016}}</ref>

==Philanthrophy and activism==
[[File:The Heart Truth's Red Dress Collection 2004.jpg|thumb|Thalía (third from left in the front) with other celebrities at The Heart Truth's Red Dress Collection in 2006]]
Thalía has participated in various humanitarian campaigns. Since 2004, she has been an official celebrity ambassador and volunteer of [[March of Dimes]], to support national fundraising and awareness campaigns. [[March of Dimes]] is a United States nonprofit organization that works to improve the health of mothers and babies.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nacersano.org/prematuro/9322_10434.asp|title=Inicio – Nacersano|access-date=31 October 2014}}</ref> Also, since 2016 she is a [[List of UNICEF Goodwill Ambassadors|UNICEF Mexico Ambassador]].<ref name="UNICEF"/> Thalía is also became a member of "[[ALAS Foundation]]", which is a non-profit organization that strives to launch a new social movement that will generate a collective commitment to comprehensive Early Childhood Development programs for the children in Latin America.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.lasnoticiasmexico.com/112925.html|title=U2 y shakira en mexico en concierto en fundacion ALAS fotos|access-date=31 October 2014}}</ref>

Through various public service campaigns and through her own media channels, Thalia has been a strong voice for March of Dimes Prematurity Campaign. She also is featured in March of Dimes Education and Health Promotion materials in English and Spanish, while she has helped to raise awareness and critical funds for the March of Dimes year-round. Furthermore, she supports March for Babies and works to find ongoing opportunities for March of Dimes strategic alliances and media promotions.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.marchofdimes.org/spotlights/spotlight-on-thalia.aspx|title=Home – March of Dimes|access-date=11 November 2014}}</ref>
<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.esmas.com/espectaculos/farandula/486899.html|title=Thalia busca salvar niños|access-date=31 October 2014|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131029191408/http://www.esmas.com/espectaculos/farandula/486899.html|archive-date=29 October 2013}}</ref>

In 2006, Thalía along with her husband attended the event ''A Funny Thing Happened on the Way To Cure Parkinson's'' with the aim to economically support the foundation ''The Michael J. Fox Foundation for Parkinson's Research'' of [[Michael J. Fox]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.labotana.com/index.php/celebridades/14627-0737-christian-chavez-no-quiere-ser-vocero-oficial-de-la-comunidad-gay|title=Página Principal – LaBotana.com – Noticias y chismes de los famosos|access-date=31 October 2014}}{{Dead link|date=November 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hola.com/noticias-de-actualidad/06-11-2008/60900/|title=Thalia muestra su apoyo incondicional a la Fundación de Michael J. Fox para la inve |work=us.hola.com|access-date=31 October 2014}}</ref> In May 2009, Thalía and Tommy Mottola were recognized from St. Jude Children's Research Hospital in Miami for their support in children in need.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.elporvenir.com.mx/notas.asp?nota_id%3D304644 |title=El Porvenir &#124;El Tren / El Tren &#124;Reconocerán filantropía de Talía |access-date=7 November 2012 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131030014447/http://www.elporvenir.com.mx/notas.asp?nota_id=304644 |archive-date=30 October 2013}}</ref> In 2010, she reunited with other recording artists, performers and actors like [[Sharon Stone]], [[Michael Douglas]], [[Jennifer Lopez]] and [[Marc Anthony]] between others, to raise funds for the "Foundation of the New York's police department", which works for better urban security.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.quien.com/espectaculos/2010/03/18/thalia-apoya-a-la-policia-de-ny|title=Thalia apoya a la policía de NY|date=18 March 2010|access-date=31 October 2014}}</ref> In 2011, she attended a beneficial event in New York, organized by the ''Robin Hood Foundation'' with the aim to raise money for homeless youth.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.antena3.com/celebrities/famosos-fiesta/celebrities-acuden-gala-fundacion-robin-hood_2011051002237.html|title=Thalía, embarazadísima y solidaria|date=7 January 2013|work=Antena3.com|access-date=31 October 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.quien.com/fotogalerias/2011/05/10/thalia-en-la-gala-de-la-fundacion-robin-hood|title=Quien.com : Thalía en la gala de la Fundación Robin Hood|date=10 May 2011|access-date=31 October 2014}}</ref> In the same year, she closed the Mexican [[Teletón (Mexico)|Teleton]] by offering a live concert.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www2.esmas.com/entretenimiento/musica/noticias/372910/thalia-cerrara-teleton-2011|title=Thalia cerrará Teletón 2011|website=Esmas.com|access-date=31 October 2014|archive-date=22 November 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121122095054/http://www2.esmas.com/entretenimiento/musica/noticias/372910/thalia-cerrara-teleton-2011|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://entretenimiento.starmedia.com/musica/concierto-thalia-en-cierre-teleton-2011.html|title=Concierto de Thalía en cierre del Teletón 2011|work=starMedia|access-date=31 October 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151018143758/http://entretenimiento.starmedia.com/musica/concierto-thalia-en-cierre-teleton-2011.html|archive-date=18 October 2015|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://noticiasespectaculos.info/teleton-2011-supero-la-meta-recaudando-471-472925-pesos/|title=Teletón 2011 supero la meta recaudando $471.472,925 pesos|work=Noticias De Espectaculos|access-date=31 October 2014|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130530215110/http://noticiasespectaculos.info/teleton-2011-supero-la-meta-recaudando-471-472925-pesos/|archive-date=30 May 2013}}</ref>

In November 2012, Thalía took humanitarian aid and comfort to compatriots of her in New York that were affected by [[Hurricane Sandy]]. She stated : "When I started seeing the destruction of Sandy I thought it was incredible, but, when I saw my Mexican brothers and sisters I felt the need to try and do something for them" in front of a group of families gathered at the Staten Island Immigrant Information Center in one of the most devastated by the storm areas. She went on to say that in times like this an artist should use the reach of the media to collect aid for the victims, and at the same time she called on the public to deposit money in the account opened by the Mexican Consulate for that purpose.<ref>{{cite news | url=http://latino.foxnews.com/latino/news/2012/11/09/thalia-distributes-aid-to-mexican-immigrants-affected-by-sandy/#ixzz2BlZQYZKU | work=Fox News | title=Thalia distributes aid to Mexican immigrants affected by Sandy | date=9 November 2012 | url-status=dead | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131029200619/http://latino.foxnews.com/latino/news/2012/11/09/thalia-distributes-aid-to-mexican-immigrants-affected-by-sandy/#ixzz2BlZQYZKU | archive-date=29 October 2013 | df=dmy-all }}</ref>

In April 2013, Thalía was awarded with the "Your Voice Inspires Many" award by the ''Lyme Research Alliance''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://thaliaforever.com/2013/04/07/foto-thalia-attends-time-for-lyme-gala-06-04-2013/ |title=HQ Fotos: Thalia attends "Time for Lyme Gala" (06.04.2013) &#124; Fan Club Oficial, "Thalia Forever" Romania |access-date=31 October 2014 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131208173703/http://thaliaforever.com/2013/04/07/foto-thalia-attends-time-for-lyme-gala-06-04-2013/ |archive-date=8 December 2013}}</ref>

==Personal life==
[[File:Thalia and Tommy Mottola.png|thumb|left|Thalía kissing her husband, Tommy Mottola at her Macy's Thalía Collection]]
Thalía was in a relationship with actor [[Fernando Colunga]] from 1995 to 1996 while they appeared on the series ''[[María la del Barrio]]''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://wapa.pe/entretenimiento/1533392-thalia-confirma-romance-fernando-colunga-video-viral-revive-momento-instagram-novelas-televisa-parejas-famosos-mexicanos-mexico-fotogaleria/amp|title=El día en que Thalía confirmó su romance con Fernando Colunga [VIDEO]}}</ref> Thalía married music executive [[Tommy Mottola]] <!--in New York City at [[St. Patrick's Cathedral, New York|St. Patrick's Cathedral]]--> on 2 December 2000.<ref>{{Cite news | title=Thalía is pregnant! | url=http://www.peopleenespanol.com/pespanol/en/articles/0,22490,1722075_1632035,00.html | work=[[People en Español]] | date=12 June 2007 | quote=The couple was married on Dec. 2, 2000 in New York. | url-status=dead | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20091106100743/http://www.peopleenespanol.com/pespanol/en/articles/0,22490,1722075_1632035,00.html | archive-date=6 November 2009 | df=dmy-all }} The article appears in English. '''Note:''' The U.S. edition of ''[[People (magazine)|People]]'' gives the wedding date as 11 October 1997: {{cite news| url=http://www.people.com/people/article/0,,621423,00.html| title=Music Mogul Marries| first=Stephen M.| last=Silverman| date=13 October 1997| work=People| access-date=24 June 2015}}</ref> The couple have two children, a daughter born in October 2007,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://celebritybabies.people.com/2007/10/08/thalia-and-tomm/ |work=People |title=Thalía and Tommy Mottola welcome daughter Sabrina Sakaë |date=8 October 2007 |access-date=24 June 2015 |archive-date=26 June 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150626152430/http://celebritybabies.people.com/2007/10/08/thalia-and-tomm/ |url-status=dead }}</ref> and a son born in June 2011.<ref>{{cite news| url= http://celebritybabies.people.com/2011/06/25/thalia-welcomes-son-matthew-alejandro/| work= People| title= Thalía Welcomes Son Matthew Alejandro| date= 25 June 2011| access-date= 24 June 2015| archive-date= 25 June 2015| archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20150625194104/http://celebritybabies.people.com/2011/06/25/thalia-welcomes-son-matthew-alejandro/| url-status= dead}}</ref> Thalía has stated in her autobiography and elsewhere that she is religious and believes profoundly in God. She began studying [[Kabbalah]] in 2002, using many of its symbols in the artwork of her album ''[[El Sexto Sentido]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thalia.com/elsextosentido/ |title=Thalía – El Sexto Sentido |access-date=31 October 2014 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140718051932/http://thalia.com/elsextosentido/ |archive-date=18 July 2014}}</ref> In 2015 she accidentally revealed during an interview that she had multiple miscarriages which caused her depression and were some of the hardest times in her life.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.latintimes.com/thalia-accidentally-confesses-miscarriage-during-interview-el-gordo-y-la-flaca-310972|title=Thalía Accidentally Confesses Miscarriage During Interview With 'El Gordo Y La Flaca'|first=Janel|last=Saldana|date=22 April 2015|website=Latin Times}}</ref>

In September 2002, Thalía's sisters, Laura Zapata and Ernestina Sodi, were kidnapped in Mexico City. Zapata was released 18 days after her kidnapping, and her sister Ernestina was released on the 36th day.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.nytimes.com/2002/10/29/world/world-briefing-the-americas-mexico-kidnapped-writer-freed.html | work=The New York Times  | title=Kidnapped writer freed | date=29 October 2002}}</ref><ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.nytimes.com/2002/10/12/world/world-briefing-americas-mexico-kidnapped-actress-freed.html | work=[[The New York Times]]| title=Kidnapped actress freed | date=12 October 2002}}</ref> Thalía has had a series of familial conflicts, especially with her sister [[Laura Zapata]]. She has opted to keep her point of view regarding to her familial issues private, despite the attacks she has received from her older sister.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.elnuevodia.com/thaliausalamusicaparasanar-1364529.html|title=Home|work=El Nuevo Dia|access-date=31 October 2014|archive-date=18 November 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121118201156/http://www.elnuevodia.com/thaliausalamusicaparasanar-1364529.html|url-status=dead}}</ref> In a press interview, Thalía stated that her familial problems with her sister are "just a dark cloud in a shiny sky".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://entretenimiento.univision.com/chismes/noticias/article/2012-10-18/los-problemas-familiares-no-afectan-a-thalia|title=Para Thalía sus problemas familiares son como ''una nubecita tapándole el sol''|work=Univision.com|access-date=31 October 2014}}</ref>

In 2008, Thalía was affected by [[Lyme disease]], a disease commonly transmitted by [[ticks]]. The illness prevented her from promoting her album [[Lunada (album)|Lunada]], while it functioned as a motivation for her to have a totally different perspective towards life.<ref name="lymedisease.org">{{cite web|url=http://lymedisease.org/news/touchedbylyme/thalia.html|title=Touched by Time: (book review) Thalia "growing stronger" after Lyme |work=LymeDisease.org|date=2 January 2012|access-date=31 October 2014}}</ref>
In reference to her illness, Thalía stated in her autobiography : "I would sweat profusely, soaking my pajamas, the sheets and even the mattress; everything hurt, even my hair, which, by the way, started to fall out. At times it felt as if my head were going to burst, as if there were lead inside of it; my eyes ached in their sockets....the hypersensitivity of my skin was so severe that sometimes I couldn't even handle the bed sheets."<ref name="lymedisease.org"/>

==Influences==
According to Thalia herself, her major personal influence was her mother, who was a motivating manager for Thalia from the very beginning of her career until 2000.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://entretenimiento.univision.com/fotos/populares/slideshow/2011-05-27/miranda-con-thalia-y-sus-hijas-en-foto |title=Los momentos de Miranda con Thalía y sus hijas |publisher=Univision Entretenimiento |access-date=22 October 2012}}</ref> As for her artistic influences, Thalia's work is mostly influenced by [[Gloria Estefan]], [[Celine Dion]], [[Sade (band)|Sade]], [[Billie Holiday]], [[Frank Sinatra]], [[The Doors]], and [[Kylie Minogue]],<ref name="abullseyeview"/> while she has stated that she always admired [[Marilyn Monroe]] and [[Madonna]]. Thalia's first idol, according to her, was athlete [[Nadia Comaneci]]. She has even stated that her record-breaking performance was a huge motivation for her to follow a career in entertainment.

==Cultural impact==
[[File:Thalia and Barack Obama cropped.jpg|thumb|right|250px|Thalía with [[Barack Obama]] singing "[[Amor a la Mexicana (song)|Amor a la Mexicana]]" at the White House. Thalía helped to globalize and popularize [[Culture of Mexico|Mexican culture]] with the [[Amor a la Mexicana|album of the same name]].<ref name="1B">{{cite magazine|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/latin/9463772/thalia-songs-billboard-charts/|title=Thalia's 10 Best Songs on the Billboard Charts, In Honor of Hispanic Heritage Month|magazine=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|date=October 11, 2020|access-date=January 7, 2021|first=Lucas|last=Villa|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201016010410/https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/latin/9463772/thalia-songs-billboard-charts/|archive-date=2020-10-16}}</ref> Diverses authors named her the most "important" or "influential" Mexican female artist.]]

She is referred as the "[[Honorific nicknames in popular music|Queen of Latin Pop]]" by international media at least since the early-2000s,<ref name="Time2">{{cite magazine|url=http://www.time.com/time/arts/article/0,8599,94188-1,00.html|title=The Mrs. Mottola Nobody Knows|magazine=[[Time (magazine)|Time]]|date=January 8, 2001|access-date=January 18, 2022|pages=1–3|first=Ed|last=Grant|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20050923204121/http://www.time.com/time/arts/article/0,8599,94188-1,00.html|archive-date=September 23, 2005|quote=Mariah's successor is the Queen of Latin Pop}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=QjW3AAAAIAAJ&q=Thal%C3%ADa+Queen+of+Latin+Pop|title=News: Analysis & Commentary|work=[[Business Week]]|date=2002|access-date=June 24, 2020|issue=3797–3801|quote=Industry sources say the queen of Latin pop will lend her name to a new line of clothing, shoes, and cosmetics for Kmart. Although unknown to many English-speaking Americans, Thalia (pronounced Tah-lee-ah)...}}</ref> and was named by ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'' during the late-1990s as "Latin American's Reigning Music Queen".<ref name=Billboard/> Thalía's success and impact in [[Latin music]] has been noted and praised by many critics. According to ''Billboard'', she has achieved critical acclaim and commercial success as both a singer and songwriter,<ref name="Start"/> and has remained as one of the leading female artists in Latin music.<ref name="1B"/> Before her crossover attempt to the English market with a [[Thalía (English album)|homonymous album]] in 2003, she gained success with her Spanish recordings in Europe, Asia and all over the Americas, even before the crossover of contemporaries artists such as [[Enrique Iglesias]], [[Ricky Martin]], [[Shakira]] and [[Paulina Rubio]]. She also stated: "My internationalization has come for several years ago and in Spanish, which is very significant".<ref name="ElUNIVERSO">{{cite web |url=https://www.eluniverso.com/2002/05/20/0001/259/DD0FC743F6DE4541B0E372B0EFF903A4.html|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200625055214/https://www.eluniverso.com/2002/05/20/0001/259/DD0FC743F6DE4541B0E372B0EFF903A4.html|url-status=dead|archive-date=25 June 2020|title=Thalía asegura que conquistar mercado EEUU no le quita el sueño|work=[[El Universo]]|date=20 May 2002|access-date=January 18, 2022|author=[[EFE]]}}</ref> Thalía was included in ''Billboard'' list the "Greatest Latin Artists of All Time" in 2020.<ref name="BBLatin"/>

According to the American magazine ''[[Ocean Drive (magazine)|Ocean Drive]]'', Thalía is "the biggest star Mexico has exported in the last decades".<ref name="OceanDrive">{{cite web|url=http://archivo.laprensa.com.ni/archivo/2001/noviembre/09/aquientrenos/diversion/diversion-20011109-04.html|title=Farándula: Thalía arrasando con todo|work=[[La Prensa (Managua)|La Prensa]]|location=Managua, Nicaragua|first=Manuel|last=Santelices|editor=[[Ocean Drive (magazine)|Ocean Drive]]|year=2001|access-date=January 18, 2022|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130614172645/http://archivo.laprensa.com.ni/archivo/2001/noviembre/09/aquientrenos/diversion/diversion-20011109-04.html|archive-date=14 June 2013}}</ref> Similarly, Tammy Gagne in ''We Visit Mexico'' (2010) described her as "the most popular singer, actress, and dancer in Mexico",<ref name="Tammy">{{cite book|url=https://www.google.com/books/edition/We_Visit_Mexico/qriXBgAAQBAJ?hl=en&gbpv=1&dq=|title=Famous People in Mexico: Thalía|work=We Visit Mexico|first=Tammy|last=Gagne|publisher=Mitchell Lane Publishers, Incorporated|date=2010|page=49|isbn=9781612280417|access-date=January 18, 2022}}</ref> while [[Rough Guides]] discussed the [[Latin pop music]] stage in Latin America saying that in [[Mexican pop music|Mexico]], "since the 1990s the biggest name has been Thalía".<ref name="APA">{{cite book|url=https://www.google.com/books/edition/The_Rough_Guide_to_Mexico_Travel_Guide_e/X5enDwAAQBAJ?hl=en&gbpv=1&dq=|title=Mexican popand "Latin Alternative"|work=The Rough Guide to Mexico|publisher=[[Apa Publications]]|date=2019|isbn=9781789196191|access-date=January 18, 2022|quote=Since the 1990s the biggest name has been Thalía.}}</ref> [[Univision]] placed Thalía at number 8 in their list of "25 most influential Mexican musicians",<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.oyemexico.com/nota/25-mexicanos-mas-influyentes-en-la-musica/|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130412053344/http://www.oyemexico.com/nota/25-mexicanos-mas-influyentes-en-la-musica/|url-status=dead|archive-date=12 April 2013|title=25 mexicanos mas influyentes en la música |publisher=Oyemexico.com |access-date=January 18, 2022}}</ref> the highest peak by a female artist within the list.

Thalía has been also described as an influential Latin woman,<ref name="MSN20">{{cite web |url=https://www.msn.com/es-co/noticias/otras/%C2%BFpor-qu%C3%A9-thalia-es-un-icono-latino/ss-BB1dhN1b|archive-url=|archive-date=|title=¿Por qué Thalia es un icono latino?|publisher=[[MSN]]|date=March 3, 2021|access-date=January 18, 2022|language=es}}</ref> and has been part of diverse [[listicle]]s. For instance, ''[[People en Español]]'' included her in their book ''Legends: the 100 most iconic Hispanic entertainers of all time'' (2008).<ref name="PHispanis">{{cite book|url=https://archive.org/details/legends100mostic0000unse/page/8/mode/2up?q=Thal%C3%ADa|title=Thalía|work=Legends: the 100 most iconic Hispanic entertainers of all time|publisher=[[Penguin Group|Celebra Books]]|date=2008|access-date=February 7, 2022|page=194|isbn=9780451225177|language=es, en|via=Archive.org|url-access=limited}}</ref> The same magazine, include her at their "The 25 Most Influential Latin Women" and [[Terra Networks]] named her one of the most "powerful and iconic women in music" in 2011.<ref name="LatinWomen">{{cite web |url=https://peopleenespanol.com/gallery/25-most-influential-latin-women/?slide=171280|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200624235525/https://peopleenespanol.com/gallery/25-most-influential-latin-women/?slide=171280|url-status=dead|archive-date=June 24, 2020|title=The 25 Most Influential Latin Women|work=[[People en Español]]|date=August 31, 2010|access-date=January 18, 2022|language=es}}</ref><ref name="Terra Networks Influential">{{cite news|url=http://musica.terra.com/las-mujeres-mas-fuertes-e-iconicas-de-la-musica,aa86dad93eee5310VgnVCM20000099f154d0RCRD.html|title=Las mujeres más fuertes e icónicas de la música|work=[[Terra Networks]]|date=8 March 2012|access-date=11 August 2012|page=2|language=es|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120311195419/http://musica.terra.com/las-mujeres-mas-fuertes-e-iconicas-de-la-musica,aa86dad93eee5310VgnVCM20000099f154d0RCRD.html|archive-date=11 March 2012}}</ref> [[Leila Cobo]] from ''Billboard'' wrote she "has carved out one of the most successful global Latin careers in memory".<ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ERUEAAAAMBAJ&q=Thal%C3%ADa+Queen+of+Soap+Operas&pg=PA29|title=THALÍA|magazine=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|date=January 18, 2022|access-date=January 18, 2022|page=27|volume=117|issue=43|issn=0006-2510|last=Cobo|first=Leila|author-link=Leila Cobo}}</ref> Producer [[Emilio Estefan]] called her "Mexico's diva of divas" and stated "Thalía is one of the few female artists in the Latino market who has legions of fans throughout Latin America, including Brazil".<ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=GgoEAAAAMBAJ&q=Thal%C3%ADa+gold+platinum&pg=PA68|title=EMILIOS'S WHO'S WHO: THALÍA|magazine=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|date=26 September 1998|access-date=January 18, 2022|page=68|volume=110|issue=39|issn=0006-2510}}</ref> In 1998, French company [[Louis Vuitton]] invited her to appear in ''Rebonds'' publication, being at the time the first Latin celebrity to appear in that book.<ref>{{cite web|first=Sandra |last=Rodríguez |url=http://www.terra.com.mx/entretenimiento/articulo/18798/Es+Thalia+la+unica+latina+en+Rebonds.htm |title=Es Thalía la única latina en 'Rebonds' – Música – Gente E |publisher=Terra |access-date=January 18, 2022}}</ref> In 1997, 25 April was declared by the [[government of Los Angeles]], as "Thalia's National Day", because of her growing popularity among the [[Hispanic and Latino Americans|Latino community in the United States]].<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=STjcB_f7CVcC&q=thalia&pg=PA835 |title=Encyclopedia of Latino Popular Culture – Cordelia Candelaria, Peter J. García, Arturo J. Aldama |access-date=January 18, 2022|isbn=9780313332104 |last1=Candelaria |first1=Cordelia |year=2004 }}</ref>

Thalia's rise to international prominence coincided with the worldwide broadcast of the soap operas she starred in. [[Thalía filmography|Her soap operas]] were viewed in more than 180 countries by almost 2&nbsp;billion viewers according to [[UNICEF]],<ref name="UNICEF">{{cite web |url=https://www.unicef.org/media/media_91813.html|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200106024021/https://www.unicef.org/media/media_91813.html|url-status=dead|archive-date=6 January 2020|title=Award-winning artist Thalía appointed UNICEF Mexico Ambassador|publisher=[[UNICEF]]|date=8 July 2016|access-date=January 18, 2022}}</ref> and many of her ''telenovelas'' became one of [[List of most-watched television broadcasts|the most watched television broadcasts]] around the world. She is known as the "Queen of ''Telenovelas''" ("Queen of Soap Operas") and ''Billboard'' once named her "the most widely recognized Spanish-speaking soap star in the world".<ref name="Start"/><ref name="RS">{{cite magazine |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-latin/thalia-valiente-lindo-pero-bruto-timbiriche-796556/|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200407170335/https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-latin/thalia-valiente-lindo-pero-bruto-timbiriche-796556/|url-status=dead|archive-date=7 April 2020|title=Thalía on Embracing Girl Power, Turning the Tables in Latin Pop|magazine=[[Rolling Stone]]|date=21 February 2019|access-date=January 18, 2022|first=Isabela|last=Raygoza}}</ref> She also gained success as a businesswoman,<ref name=Billboard/> with commercial and critical recognition for her business ventures by launching several products under her brand name,<ref>{{cite web |author=Josué P. Camacho / El Mexicano |url=http://www.el-mexicano.com.mx/informacion/noticias/1/8/fama/2011/07/23/489329/sigue-cosechando-exitos.aspx |title=2011/07/23 Sigue cosechando éxitos -El Mexicano |publisher=El-mexicano.com.mx |date=23 July 2011 |access-date=January 18, 2022|archive-date=14 May 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130514091746/http://www.el-mexicano.com.mx/informacion/noticias/1/8/fama/2011/07/23/489329/sigue-cosechando-exitos.aspx |url-status=dead }}</ref> and dominated the editorial business by writing and releasing three books, that became bestsellers.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://archive.org/details/thaliabellezales0000thal|title=Thalia belleza!: lessons in lipgloss and happiness|date=2007|publisher=Chronicle Books|last=Aranda-Alvarado|first= Belén|isbn=9780811858298|location=San Francisco|oclc=123539377|url-access=registration}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|title=Thalia : ¡radiante! : your guide to a fit and fabulous pregnancy|last=Thalía.|others=Kramer, Andrew R.|isbn=9780811858120|location=San Francisco|oclc=213855397|date = April 2009}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|title=Growing stronger|date=2011|publisher=New American Library|isbn=9780451234414|location=New York|oclc=743214703}}</ref> According to Felipe Escudero from ''[[El Mundo (Spain)|El Mundo]]'' in 2006, Thalía was described as the "Latin [[Madonna]] of the Hispanic market" and a "Queen [[Midas]]" due her success as a businesswoman.<ref name="Midas">{{cite web |url=https://www.elmundo.es/suplementos/magazine/2006/329/1137178953.html|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180827205936/https://www.elmundo.es/suplementos/magazine/2006/329/1137178953.html|url-status=dead|archive-date=27 August 2018|title=Ahora, el pueblo latino se ha convertido en una prioridad para EEUU porque generamos dinero|work=[[El Mundo (Spain)|El Mundo]]|location=Spain|date=15 January 2006|access-date=January 18, 2022|language=es|first=Felipe|last=Escudero}}</ref>

Thalía is considered a [[gay icon]] and according to [[Infobae]], many of her fans recognized her as the "Latin queen of [[LGBT community|gay community]]". The same publication also stated Thalía is one of the most "emulated pop singers by transvestite shows in [[Gay bar|gay nightclubs]]".<ref name="INFOBAE">{{cite web |url=https://www.infobae.com/america/entretenimiento/2019/05/22/thalia-y-su-homenaje-a-la-comunidad-lgbtq-con-mensajes-a-favor-de-la-diversidad/|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190530222355/https://www.infobae.com/america/entretenimiento/2019/05/22/thalia-y-su-homenaje-a-la-comunidad-lgbtq-con-mensajes-a-favor-de-la-diversidad/|url-status=dead|archive-date=30 May 2019|title=Thalía y su homenaje a la comunidad LGBTQ con mensajes a favor de la diversidad|publisher=[[Infobae]]|date=22 May 2019|access-date=January 18, 2022|language=es}}</ref> Andrés del Real from ''[[La Tercera]]'' felt she is an icon for the [[sexual minority]],<ref name="Tercera">{{cite web |url=https://www.latercera.com/culto/2018/06/16/thalia-mi-carrera-ha-sido-camaleonica-he-escuchado-a-gente-distinta/|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200624230009/https://www.latercera.com/culto/2018/06/16/thalia-mi-carrera-ha-sido-camaleonica-he-escuchado-a-gente-distinta/|url-status=dead|archive-date=January 18, 2022|title=Thalía: "Mi carrera ha sido camaleónica porque he escuchado a gente distinta"|work=[[La Tercera]]|date=16 June 2018|access-date=January 18, 2022|language=es|first=Andrés|last=Del Real}}</ref> and professor Ramón García in ''Chicano Representation and the Strategies of Modernism'' (1997) wrote Thalía is "the dream identity of many drag queens".<ref name="Garcia">{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=hXshAQAAIAAJ&q=Singing+sex-bomb+Thalia,+the+dream+identity+of+many+drag+queen|quote=Singing sex-bomb Thalia, the dream identity of many drag queen|title=Chicano Representation and the Strategies of Modernism|publisher=[[University of California, San Diego]]|date=1997|access-date=January 18, 2022|page=65|first=Ramón|last=García}}</ref> Ed Grant from ''[[Time (magazine)|Time]]'' also commented that many of them called themselves "Thalíos".<ref name="Time2"/>

Thalia has been an influential artist for almost every younger Latin pop singer, including [[Anahí]], [[Belinda]], and urban Latin artists [[Becky G]], [[Natti Natasha]] and [[Karol G]] among others,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.tvynovelas.com/noticias/us/493591/thalia-y-anahi-se-juerga-/|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120904012953/http://www.tvynovelas.com/noticias/us/493591/thalia-y-anahi-se-juerga-/|url-status=dead|archive-date=4 September 2012|title=¡THALÍA Y ANAHÍ SE VAN DE PARRANDA!|work=[[TVyNovelas]]|date=30 August 2012|access-date=January 18, 2022|language=es}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.univision.com/especiales/premio-lo-nuestro/la-sencillez-y-carrera-de-thalia-es-inspiracion-para-becky-g-video|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200624220937/https://www.univision.com/especiales/premio-lo-nuestro/la-sencillez-y-carrera-de-thalia-es-inspiracion-para-becky-g-video|url-status=dead|archive-date=January 18, 2022|title=La sencillez y carrera de Thalía es inspiración para Becky G|publisher=[[Univision]]|date=17 February 2015|access-date=January 18, 2022|language=es}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://us.hola.com/es/celebrities/20191126figdcutjas/natti-natasha-daddy-yankee-influencias-musicales|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200411135244/https://us.hola.com/es/celebrities/20191126figdcutjas/natti-natasha-daddy-yankee-influencias-musicales|url-status=dead|archive-date=11 April 2020|title=NATTI NATASHA HABLA SOBRE CÓMO TRABAJAR CON DADDY YANKEE, THALÍA Y MÁS AYUDÓ A DAR FORMA A SU CARRERA|work=[[¡Hola!]]|date=30 March 2020|access-date=January 18, 2022|language=es}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://elcomercio.pe/tvmas/famosos/karol-g-confeso-que-thalia-fue-su-primer-icono-musical-video-instagram-nndc-noticia/|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200624220119/https://elcomercio.pe/tvmas/famosos/karol-g-confeso-que-thalia-fue-su-primer-icono-musical-video-instagram-nndc-noticia/|url-status=dead|archive-date=January 18, 2022|title=Karol G confesó que Thalía fue su primer ícono musical|work=[[El Comercio (Peru)|El Comercio]]|location=Peru|date=12 March 2020 |access-date=January 18, 2022|language=es}}</ref> while [[Julio Iglesias]], [[Tony Bennett]], [[Juan Luis Guerra]], [[Gloria Estefan]], [[Ricky Martin]], [[Laura Pausini]], [[Tiziano Ferro]], [[Michael Bublé]], [[Espinoza Paz]], [[Gloria Trevi]], [[Inna]], [[Erik Rubin]], [[Pedro Capó]], [[Maluma (singer)|Maluma]], [[Robbie Williams]] and many other artists have expressed their admiration towards her talent and charisma.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.terra.com/entretenimiento/noticias/Lindsay_lohan_quiere_ser_como_thalia/oci64881 |title=Lindsay Lohan quiere ser como... Thalía! |publisher=Terra |access-date=January 18, 2022}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://laprimeraplana.com.mx/2011/09/21/espinoza-paz-quiere-grabar-dueto-con-thalia/ |title=Espinoza Paz quiere grabar dueto con Thalía |publisher=La Primera Plana |date=22 September 2011 |access-date=January 18, 2022 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131029192438/http://laprimeraplana.com.mx/2011/09/21/espinoza-paz-quiere-grabar-dueto-con-thalia/ |archive-date=29 October 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author=El Siglo de Torreón|url=http://www.elsiglodetorreon.com.mx/noticia/89772.tiziano-ferro-quiere-componer-para-thalia.html |title=Tiziano Ferro quiere componer para Thalía / Espectáculos |publisher=Elsiglodetorreon.com.mx |date=22 May 2004 |access-date=January 18, 2022}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.imagendelgolfo.com.mx/resumen.php?id=301599 |title=Inna viene la reina del Dance Music |publisher=Agencia Imagen del Golfo |date=14 March 2012 |access-date=January 18, 2022}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=7RMEAAAAMBAJ&q=thal%C3%ADa+arrasando+billboard&pg=PA7-IA4 |title=Billboard – Google Libros |date= 18 August 2001|access-date=January 18, 2022}}</ref>

== Awards and achievements ==
{{See also|List of awards and nominations received by Thalía}}
Thalía has achieved multiple milestones during her career with her music, acting career and business ventures. Luis Magaña from ''[[El Universal (Mexico City)|El Universal]]'' commented that those record figures in her career are "impressive" and found that she has been the first in place of different situations in life.<ref name="Universal2021"/>

Thalía has sold over 25 million records worldwide,<ref name="wwsales"/> and is one of the best-selling Latin music artists. She has numerous albums amongst the [[List of best-selling Latin albums|best-selling in Spanish-language]] that include ''En éxtasis'', ''Amor a la Mexicana'' and ''Arrasando'' with sales of over 2 million copies worldwide and have at least one album amongst the best selling of all-time in [[List of best-selling albums in Mexico|Mexico]], [[List of best-selling albums in Chile|Chile]] and the [[List of best-selling albums in the Philippines|Philippines]]. "[[No Me Acuerdo]]" is also one of the [[List of best-selling Latin singles in the United States|best-selling Latin singles in the United States]]. According to [[El Universal (Mexico City)|''El Universal'']], Thalía is the first Latina to have a Top 10 in all continents,<ref name="Universal2021"/> and ''[[Arrasando]]'' led her to be the first Latin woman selling a Spanish album in Japan.<ref name="markets">{{cite journal|title=THALÍA|journal=Vértigo: Análisis y pensamiento de México|year=2001|language=es|page=58|issue=1–14|quote=MODESTAMENTE SIN HACER TANTO RUIDO como sucede con otras cantantes, Thalía alcanzó el millón de copias vendidas a nivel internacional de su disco Arrasando . Con esta producción, la intérprete mexicana ha ingresado a nuevos mercados como Canadá, Italia, Suiza, Japón (donde es la primera mujer latina que logra ingresar al mercado y vender discos), Arabia, Turquía y Lituania}}</ref> ''[[Thalía con banda: Grandes éxitos|Thalía con banda]]'' is the first album of [[banda music]] with a [[Music certification|certification]] in Spain.<ref name="BiographyMTV">{{cite web|url=http://www.mtvla.com/musica/artistas/thalia/|title=Thalía biografía|publisher=[[MTV Latin America]]|language=es|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111203121748/http://www.mtvla.com/musica/artistas/thalia/#bio|archive-date=December 3, 2011|access-date=January 17, 2022}}</ref>

Thalía's versatility signing in other languages made her the first and only Latin artist with an album recorded primarily in [[Tagalog language|Tagalog]] when she released ''[[Nandito Ako (album)|Nandito Ako]]'' in 1997.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://los40.com/los40/2019/11/15/musica/1573828927_479534.html|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200625033426/https://los40.com/los40/2019/11/15/musica/1573828927_479534.html|url-status=dead|archive-date=June 25, 2020|title=De Thalía a Sofía Reyes: Cantantes Mexicanos Que Nos Encantan (Volumen II)|first=Beatriz|last=Rodríguez Ruiz|publisher=[[Los 40]]|date=November 15, 2019|access-date=January 17, 2022|language=es}}</ref> ''[[María la del Barrio]]'' is the first ''telenovela'' translated into the Tagalog language.<ref name="Universal2021"/> Thalía became the first actress to make a trilogy of ''telenovelas'' and ''[[Quinceañera (1987 TV series)|Quinceañera]]'' is considered to be the first ''telenovela'' for a teen audience.<ref name="Universal2021"/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.unotv.com/entretenimiento/quinceanera-que-fue-de-los-protagonistas-a-33-anos-de-su-estreno/|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200828021732/https://www.unotv.com/entretenimiento/quinceanera-que-fue-de-los-protagonistas-a-33-anos-de-su-estreno/|archive-date=August 20, 2020|title=¡Y ahora…! Qué fue de los protagonistas de "Quinceañera"|publisher=UNO TV|date=August 24, 2020|access-date=January 17, 2022|language=es}}</ref> Moreover, Thalía is the highest paid actress in the history of Televisa.<ref name="Paid">{{cite magazine|url=https://www.google.com/books/edition/Latina/wS0rAQAAIAAJ?hl=en|title=Thalía|access-date=January 17, 2022|magazine=[[Latina (magazine)|Latina]]|volume=10|page=106|date=2005|quote=the highest-paid actress in Televisa history}}</ref> With ''[[El Sexto Sentido]]'', Thalía set a record for the largest number of interviews granted to an electronic medium, Televisa.<ref name="Jornada">{{cite web|url=https://www.jornada.com.mx/2005/09/23/index.php?section=opinion&article=a06o1cul|title=Los tropiezos de Thalía|work=[[La Jornada]]|date=23 September 2005|access-date=January 11, 2022|language=es}}</ref> The album also became the first Spanish-language release in the United States to have a preorder campaign through [[iTunes]] and was the most expensive Spanish album up that time.<ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ERUEAAAAMBAJ&q=The+album+was+also+the+first+Spanish-language+release+in+the+United+States+to+have+a+preorder+campaign+through+iTunes&pg=PA40|title=GLOBAL SUCCESS (cont.)|magazine=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|date=October 22, 2005|access-date=January 17, 2022|page=40|volume=117|issue=43|issn=0006-2510|last=Cobo|first=Leila|author-link=Leila Cobo}}</ref><ref name="Jornada"/> She is also the first woman to have a [[HBO Latino]] concert special.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nydailynews.com/entertainment/music/thalia-marks-woman-score-hbo-latino-concert-special-article-1.1936226|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140911184653/https://www.nydailynews.com/entertainment/music/thalia-marks-woman-score-hbo-latino-concert-special-article-1.1936226|archive-date=September 11, 2014|title=Thalia marks first woman to score HBO Latino concert special: 'Thalia Viva Tour (En Vivo)'|work=[[New York Daily News]]|date=September 15, 2014|access-date=January 18, 2022|first=Zayda|last=Rivera}}</ref>

"[[Amor a la Mexicana (song)|Amor a la Mexicana]]" is the first Mexican song to be played in European [[dive bar]]s.<ref name="Universal2021"/> Thalía is also the first Mexican female artist to have a certification in Brazil,<ref name="SBTgoldBrazil">{{cite news|url=http://www.sbtworld.com.br/2012/06/popstar-anahi-ganha-seu-certificado-de.html|title=Popstar – Anahí Ganha seu certificado de Disco de Ouro por 'Mi Delírio' no Brasil|last=Franklin|first=Jonathan|work=[[Sistema Brasileiro de Televisão]]|publisher=[[Grupo Silvio Santos]]|access-date=January 17, 2022|location=[[Brazil]]|language=pt|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120624063508/http://www.sbtworld.com.br/2012/06/popstar-anahi-ganha-seu-certificado-de.html|archive-date=June 24, 2012|url-status=dead}}</ref> and remains the best-selling Mexican female soloist in that country.<ref name=Billboard>{{cite magazine|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=5AkEAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA33-IA3|magazine=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|first=Teresa|last=Aguilera|date=November 29, 1997|volume=109|number=48|title=Thalia Latin America's Reigning Music Queen|page=33}}</ref> She is also the first Mexican woman with a line of clothing in the United States,<ref name="VOGUEMX">{{cite web |url=https://www.vogue.mx/estilo-de-vida/articulo/thalia-sodi-biografia-canciones-exitos-y-sus-mejores-vestidos|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200518163524/https://www.vogue.mx/estilo-de-vida/articulo/thalia-sodi-biografia-canciones-exitos-y-sus-mejores-vestidos|url-status=dead|archive-date=May 18, 2020|title=Thalía: su vida, su trayectoria artística y sus canciones más exitosas|work=[[Vogue (magazine)|Vogue]]|location=Mexico|date=May 8, 2020|access-date=January 17, 2022|language=es|first=Sebastian|last=Cabrices}}</ref> as well the first Mexican woman closing bells at [[Nasdaq]].<ref name="Nasdaq">{{cite web |url=https://www.elsiglodetorreon.com.mx/noticia/203513.thalia-para-el-trafico-en-nueva-york.html|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181005112101/https://www.elsiglodetorreon.com.mx/noticia/203513.thalia-para-el-trafico-en-nueva-york.html|url-status=dead|archive-date=October 5, 2018|title=Thalía para el tráfico en Nueva York|work=[[El Siglo de Torreón]]|location=Mexico|date=March 22, 2006|access-date=January 17, 2022|language=es|author=[[Notimex]]}}</ref> Thalía became the first Mexican artist to hit one billion views on YouTube with "No Me Acuerdo".<ref name="1B"/> She also became in the first Mexican artist to have complete control over all the videos in her catalog.<ref name="Universal2021">{{cite news|url=https://www.eluniversal.com.mx/opinion/luis-magana/thalia-renueva-sus-videoclips-mas-exitosos|title=Thalía renueva sus videoclips más exitosos|work=[[El Universal (Mexico City)|El Universal]]|date=December 5, 2021|access-date=January 17, 2022|first=Luis|last=Magaña|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20211205150306/https://www.eluniversal.com.mx/opinion/luis-magana/thalia-renueva-sus-videoclips-mas-exitosos|archive-date=December 5, 2021}}</ref> Thalía is the most followed Mexican female artist in [[Spotify]],<ref name="Universal2021"/> and with most views on YouTube.<ref name="YTrecord">{{cite news|url=https://larepublica.pe/espectaculos/2019/10/19/instagramthalia-es-la-artista-femenina-mexicana-mas-vista-en-youtube-y-celebra-con-sus-seguidores/|title=Thalía es la artista femenina mexicana más vista en YouTube|work=[[La República]]|language=es|date=October 19, 2019|access-date=January 18, 2022|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191021031649/https://larepublica.pe/espectaculos/2019/10/19/instagramthalia-es-la-artista-femenina-mexicana-mas-vista-en-youtube-y-celebra-con-sus-seguidores/|archive-date=October 21, 2019}}</ref> She also held the record in Instagram until being surpassed by Danna Paola.<ref name="Paola">{{cite news|url=https://dosmundos.com/2020/01/16/danna-paola-supera-a-thalia-en-instagram/|title=Danna Paola supera a Thalía en Instagram|work=[[:es:Dos Mundos|Dos Mundos]]|date=January 16, 2020|access-date=January 18, 2022|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200930224243/https://dosmundos.com/2020/01/16/danna-paola-supera-a-thalia-en-instagram/|archive-date=September 30, 2020|language=es}}</ref>

She is the first recipient of the Star Award at the [[Billboard Latin Music Awards]] when she was honored in 2001.<ref name="Start">{{cite magazine|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=nRQEAAAAMBAJ&dq=thalia&pg=PA90|title=Thalia To Receive 'Star' Honor At Latin Awards|magazine=Billboard|date=April 21, 2001|access-date=January 17, 2022|volume=113|number=16|page=90}}</ref> She received her own star in the [[Hollywood Walk of Fame]] in 2013 as a recognition to her versatile trajectory and her impact in the world of music and entertainment.<ref name="abullseyeview"/><ref name="Hernandez"/> In doing so, Thalía became the first female singer born in Mexico with that achievement.<ref name="PRENSAHN">{{cite web |url=https://www.laprensa.hn/inicio/429630-280/thalia-recibe-su-estrella-en-el-paseo-de-la-fama-en-hollwyood|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200624232604/https://www.laprensa.hn/inicio/429630-280/thalia-recibe-su-estrella-en-el-paseo-de-la-fama-en-hollwyood|url-status=dead|archive-date=24 June 2020|title=Thalía recibe su estrella en el Paseo de la Fama en Hollwyood|work=[[La Prensa (Honduras)|La Prensa]]|location=Honduras|date=12 May 2013|access-date=24 June 2020|language=es}}</ref><ref name="HollywoodStar">{{cite web|url=https://www.sandiegouniontribune.com/en-espanol/sdhoy-an-emotional-thalia-receives-her-star-on-2013dec06-story.html|title=An emotional Thalia receives her star on Hollywood Walk of Fame|work=[[The San Diego Union-Tribune]]|author=[[EFE]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220118012336/https://www.sandiegouniontribune.com/en-espanol/sdhoy-an-emotional-thalia-receives-her-star-on-2013dec06-story.html|archive-date=January 18, 2022|access-date=January 18, 2022|date=December 6, 2013}}</ref> She also was the first Mexican singer and actress to receive a star in Miami (Calle 8, Walk of Fame) and in Venezuela she was the youngest artist to receive their walk of fame. She holds a record for appearing the most times in ''[[People en Español]]''{{'}}s annual list of the most beautiful Latin celebrities (''Los más bellos'').<ref name="LosMas">{{cite web |url=https://peopleenespanol.com/celebridades/thalia-recibe-un-premio-de-people-en-espanol/|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191004193218/https://peopleenespanol.com/celebridades/thalia-recibe-un-premio-de-people-en-espanol/|url-status=dead|archive-date=4 October 2019|title=Thalía recibe un premio muy especial en la fiesta de Bellos: "Celebremos que estamos vivos"|work=[[People en Español]]|date=May 16, 2017|access-date=January 17, 2022|first=Lena|last=Hansen|language=es}}</ref> She became the first face of [[Jacob & Co]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.jacobandco.com/thalia04a.pdf|title=Singing Superstar Thalia sings on as the first face of JACOB & Co.|publisher=[[Jacob & Co]]|date=September 27, 2004|access-date=January 17, 2022|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081001214807/http://www.jacobandco.com/thalia04a.pdf|archive-date=October 1, 2008}}</ref> and the first Latina to make a deal with [[The Hershey Company]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2004/04/09/business/media-business-advertising-hershey-for-first-time-turns-celebrity-market.html|title=THE MEDIA BUSINESS: ADVERTISING; Hershey, for the first time, turns to a celebrity to market to Hispanics.|work=[[The New York Times]]|date=April 9, 2004|access-date=January 17, 2022|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130615181423/https://www.nytimes.com/2004/04/09/business/media-business-advertising-hershey-for-first-time-turns-celebrity-market.html|archive-date=June 15, 2013|first=Nat|last=Ives}}</ref>

